var P_HTM = [];
P_HTM[1]="*Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa* **";
P_HTM[2]="*Saṃyuttanikāyo* **";
P_HTM[3]="*Dukanipāta* **";
P_HTM[4]="*2. Kammakaraṇavaggo* **";
P_HTM[5]="*2. Dutiyapaṇṇāsakaṃ**Kammakaraṇavagga*";
P_HTM[6]="*1. Vajjasuttaṃ**1. Vajjasutta*";
P_HTM[7]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[8]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[9]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[10]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[11]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[12]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[13]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, vajjāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two faults.*";
P_HTM[14]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[15]="*Diṭṭhadhammikañca vajjaṃ samparāyikañca vajjaṃ.**The fault apparent in the present life, and the fault to do with lives to come.*";
P_HTM[16]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, diṭṭhadhammikaṃ vajjaṃ?**What is the fault apparent in the present life?*";
P_HTM[17]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco passati coraṃ āgucāriṃ rājāno gahetvā vividhā kammakāraṇā kārente;**It’s when someone sees that kings have arrested a bandit, a criminal, and subjected them to various punishments—*";
P_HTM[18]="*kasāhipi tāḷente, vettehipi tāḷente, addhadaṇḍakehipi tāḷente, hatthampi chindante, pādampi chindante, hatthapādampi chindante, kaṇṇampi chindante, nāsampi chindante, kaṇṇanāsampi chindante, bilaṅgathālikampi karonte, saṅkhamuṇḍikampi karonte, rāhumukhampi karonte, jotimālikampi karonte, hatthapajjotikampi karonte, erakavattikampi karonte, cīrakavāsikampi karonte, eṇeyyakampi karonte, baḷisamaṃsikampi karonte, kahāpaṇikampi karonte, khārāpatacchikampi karonte, palighaparivattikampi karonte, palālapīṭhakampi karonte, tattenapi telena osiñcante, sunakhehipi khādāpente, jīvantampi sūle uttāsente, asināpi sīsaṃ chindante.**whipping, caning, and clubbing; cutting off hands or feet, or both; cutting off ears or nose, or both; the ‘porridge pot’, the ‘shell-shave’, the ‘demon’s mouth’, the ‘garland of fire’, the ‘burning hand’, the ‘grass blades’, the ‘bark dress’, the ‘antelope’, the ‘meat hook’, the ‘coins’, the ‘acid pickle’, the ‘twisting bar’, the ‘straw mat’; being splashed with hot oil, being fed to the dogs, being impaled alive, and being beheaded.*";
P_HTM[19]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**It occurs to them:*";
P_HTM[20]="*‘yathārūpānaṃ kho pāpakānaṃ kammānaṃ hetu coraṃ āgucāriṃ rājāno gahetvā vividhā kammakāraṇā kārenti;**‘If I were to commit the kinds of bad deeds for which the kings arrested that bandit, that criminal,*";
P_HTM[21]="*kasāhipi tāḷenti, vettehipi tāḷenti, addhadaṇḍakehipi tāḷenti, hatthampi chindanti, pādampi chindanti, hatthapādampi chindanti, kaṇṇampi chindanti, nāsampi chindanti, kaṇṇanāsampi chindanti, bilaṅgathālikampi karonti, saṅkhamuṇḍikampi karonti, rāhumukhampi karonti, jotimālikampi karonti, hatthapajjotikampi karonti, erakavattikampi karonti, cīrakavāsikampi karonti, eṇeyyakampi karonti, baḷisamaṃsikampi karonti, kahāpaṇikampi karonti, khārāpatacchikampi karonti, palighaparivattikampi karonti, palālapīṭhakampi karonti, tattenapi telena osiñcanti, sunakhehipi khādāpenti, jīvantampi sūle uttāsenti, asināpi sīsaṃ chindanti.* **";
P_HTM[22]="*Ahañceva kho pana evarūpaṃ pāpakammaṃ kareyyaṃ, mampi rājāno gahetvā evarūpā vividhā kammakāraṇā kāreyyuṃ;**the rulers would arrest me and subject me to the same punishments.*";
P_HTM[23]="*kasāhipi tāḷeyyuṃ … pe … asināpi sīsaṃ chindeyyun’ti.* **";
P_HTM[24]="*So diṭṭhadhammikassa vajjassa bhīto na paresaṃ pābhataṃ vilumpanto carati.**Afraid of the fault apparent in the present life, they do not steal the belongings of others.*";
P_HTM[25]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, diṭṭhadhammikaṃ vajjaṃ.**This is called the fault apparent in the present life.*";
P_HTM[26]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, samparāyikaṃ vajjaṃ?**What is the fault to do with lives to come?*";
P_HTM[27]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco iti paṭisañcikkhati:**It’s when someone reflects:*";
P_HTM[28]="*‘kāyaduccaritassa kho pana pāpako dukkho vipāko abhisamparāyaṃ, vacīduccaritassa pāpako dukkho vipāko abhisamparāyaṃ, manoduccaritassa pāpako dukkho vipāko abhisamparāyaṃ.**‘Bad conduct of body, speech, or mind has a bad, painful result in the next life.*";
P_HTM[29]="*Ahañceva kho pana kāyena duccaritaṃ careyyaṃ, vācāya duccaritaṃ careyyaṃ, manasā duccaritaṃ careyyaṃ.**If I conduct myself badly,*";
P_HTM[30]="*Kiñca taṃ yāhaṃ na kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**then, when my body breaks up, after death, won’t I be reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell?’*";
P_HTM[31]="*So samparāyikassa vajjassa bhīto kāyaduccaritaṃ pahāya kāyasucaritaṃ bhāveti, vacīduccaritaṃ pahāya vacīsucaritaṃ bhāveti, manoduccaritaṃ pahāya manosucaritaṃ bhāveti, suddhaṃ attānaṃ pariharati.**Afraid of the fault to do with lives to come, they give up bad conduct by way of body, speech, and mind, and develop good conduct by way of body, speech, and mind, keeping themselves pure.*";
P_HTM[32]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, samparāyikaṃ vajjaṃ.**This is called the fault to do with lives to come.*";
P_HTM[33]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve vajjāni.**These are the two faults.*";
P_HTM[34]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[35]="*‘diṭṭhadhammikassa vajjassa bhāyissāma, samparāyikassa vajjassa bhāyissāma, vajjabhīruno bhavissāma vajjabhayadassāvino’ti.**‘We will fear the fault apparent in the present life, and we will fear the fault to do with lives to come. We will fear faults, seeing the danger in faults.’*";
P_HTM[36]="*Evañhi vo, bhikkhave, sikkhitabbaṃ.**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[37]="*Vajjabhīruno, bhikkhave, vajjabhayadassāvino etaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ yaṃ parimuccissati sabbavajjehī”ti.**If you fear faults, seeing the danger in faults, you can expect to be freed from all faults.”*";
P_HTM[38]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[39]="*2. Padhānasutta**2. Endeavor*";
P_HTM[40]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, padhānāni durabhisambhavāni lokasmiṃ.**“These two endeavors are challenging in the world.*";
P_HTM[41]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[42]="*Yañca gihīnaṃ agāraṃ ajjhāvasataṃ cīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānapaccayabhesajjaparikkhārānuppadānatthaṃ padhānaṃ, yañca agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajitānaṃ sabbūpadhipaṭinissaggatthaṃ padhānaṃ.**The endeavor of laypeople staying in a home to provide robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick. And the endeavor of those gone forth from the lay life to homelessness to let go of all attachments.*";
P_HTM[43]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve padhānāni durabhisambhavāni lokasmiṃ.**These are the two endeavors that are challenging in the world.*";
P_HTM[44]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ padhānānaṃ yadidaṃ sabbūpadhipaṭinissaggatthaṃ padhānaṃ.**The better of these two endeavors is the effort to let go of all attachments.*";
P_HTM[45]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[46]="*‘sabbūpadhipaṭinissaggatthaṃ padhānaṃ padahissāmā’ti.**‘We shall endeavor to let go of all attachments.’*";
P_HTM[47]="*Evañhi vo, bhikkhave, sikkhitabban”ti.**That’s how you should train.”*";
P_HTM[48]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[49]="*3. Tapanīyasutta**3. Mortifying*";
P_HTM[50]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, dhammā tapanīyā.**“These two things, mendicants, are mortifying.*";
P_HTM[51]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[52]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekaccassa kāyaduccaritaṃ kataṃ hoti, akataṃ hoti kāyasucaritaṃ;**It’s when someone has done bad things and not done good things, by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[53]="*vacīduccaritaṃ kataṃ hoti, akataṃ hoti vacīsucaritaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[54]="*manoduccaritaṃ kataṃ hoti, akataṃ hoti manosucaritaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[55]="*So ‘kāyaduccaritaṃ me katan’ti tappati, ‘akataṃ me kāyasucaritan’ti tappati;**Thinking, ‘I’ve done bad things by way of body, speech, and mind’, they’re mortified. Thinking, ‘I haven’t done good things by way of body, speech, and mind’, they’re mortified.*";
P_HTM[56]="*‘vacīduccaritaṃ me katan’ti tappati, ‘akataṃ me vacīsucaritan’ti tappati;* **";
P_HTM[57]="*‘manoduccaritaṃ me katan’ti tappati, ‘akataṃ me manosucaritan’ti tappati.* **";
P_HTM[58]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve dhammā tapanīyā”ti.**These are the two things that are mortifying.”*";
P_HTM[59]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[60]="*4. Atapanīyasutta**4. Not Mortifying*";
P_HTM[61]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, dhammā atapanīyā.**“These two things, mendicants, are not mortifying.*";
P_HTM[62]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[63]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekaccassa kāyasucaritaṃ kataṃ hoti, akataṃ hoti kāyaduccaritaṃ;**It’s when someone has done good things and not done bad things, by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[64]="*vacīsucaritaṃ kataṃ hoti, akataṃ hoti vacīduccaritaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[65]="*manosucaritaṃ kataṃ hoti, akataṃ hoti manoduccaritaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[66]="*So ‘kāyasucaritaṃ me katan’ti na tappati, ‘akataṃ me kāyaduccaritan’ti na tappati;**Thinking, ‘I’ve done good things by way of body, speech, and mind’, they’re not mortified. Thinking, ‘I haven’t done bad things by way of body, speech, and mind’, they’re not mortified.*";
P_HTM[67]="*‘vacīsucaritaṃ me katan’ti na tappati, ‘akataṃ me vacīduccaritan’ti na tappati;* **";
P_HTM[68]="*‘manosucaritaṃ me katan’ti na tappati, ‘akataṃ me manoduccaritan’ti na tappati.* **";
P_HTM[69]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve dhammā atapanīyā”ti.**These are the two things that are not mortifying.”*";
P_HTM[70]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[71]="*5. Upaññātasutta**5. Learned for Myself*";
P_HTM[72]="*“Dvinnāhaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ upaññāsiṃ—**“Mendicants, I have learned these two things for myself—*";
P_HTM[73]="*yā ca asantuṭṭhitā kusalesu dhammesu, yā ca appaṭivānitā padhānasmiṃ.**to never be content with skillful qualities, and to never stop trying.*";
P_HTM[74]="*Appaṭivānī sudāhaṃ, bhikkhave, padahāmi:**I never stopped trying, thinking:*";
P_HTM[75]="*‘kāmaṃ taco ca nhāru ca aṭṭhi ca avasissatu, sarīre upassussatu maṃsalohitaṃ, yaṃ taṃ purisathāmena purisavīriyena purisaparakkamena pattabbaṃ na taṃ apāpuṇitvā vīriyassa saṇṭhānaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘Gladly, let only skin, sinews, and bones remain! Let the flesh and blood waste away in my body! I will not stop trying until I have achieved what is possible by manly strength, energy, and vigor.’*";
P_HTM[76]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, appamādādhigatā sambodhi, appamādādhigato anuttaro yogakkhemo.**It was by diligence that I achieved awakening, and by diligence that I achieved the supreme sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[77]="*Tumhe cepi, bhikkhave, appaṭivānaṃ padaheyyātha:**If you too never stop trying, thinking:*";
P_HTM[78]="*‘kāmaṃ taco ca nhāru ca aṭṭhi ca avasissatu, sarīre upassussatu maṃsalohitaṃ, yaṃ taṃ purisathāmena purisavīriyena purisaparakkamena pattabbaṃ na taṃ apāpuṇitvā vīriyassa saṇṭhānaṃ bhavissatī’ti, tumhepi, bhikkhave, nacirasseva—**‘Gladly, let only skin, sinews, and bones remain! Let the flesh and blood waste away in my body! I will not stop trying until I have achieved what is possible by manly strength, energy, and vigor.’*";
P_HTM[79]="*yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissatha.**You will soon realize the supreme culmination of the spiritual path in this very life. You will live having achieved with your own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[80]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[81]="*‘appaṭivānaṃ padahissāma.**‘We will never stop trying, thinking:*";
P_HTM[82]="*Kāmaṃ taco ca nhāru ca aṭṭhi ca avasissatu, sarīre upassussatu maṃsalohitaṃ, yaṃ taṃ purisathāmena purisavīriyena purisaparakkamena pattabbaṃ na taṃ apāpuṇitvā vīriyassa saṇṭhānaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**“Gladly, let only skin, sinews, and bones remain! Let the flesh and blood waste away in my body! I will not stop trying until I have achieved what is possible by manly strength, energy, and vigor.”’*";
P_HTM[83]="*Evañhi vo, bhikkhave, sikkhitabban”ti.**That’s how you should train.”*";
P_HTM[84]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[85]="*6. Saṃyojanasutta**6. Fetters*";
P_HTM[86]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, dhammā.**“There are, mendicants, these two things.*";
P_HTM[87]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[88]="*Yā ca saṃyojaniyesu dhammesu assādānupassitā, yā ca saṃyojaniyesu dhammesu nibbidānupassitā.**Seeing things that are prone to being fettered as gratifying, and seeing things that are prone to being fettered as boring.*";
P_HTM[89]="*Saṃyojaniyesu, bhikkhave, dhammesu assādānupassī viharanto rāgaṃ na pajahati, dosaṃ na pajahati, mohaṃ na pajahati.**When you keep seeing things that are prone to being fettered as gratifying, you don’t give up greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[90]="*Rāgaṃ appahāya, dosaṃ appahāya, mohaṃ appahāya na parimuccati jātiyā jarāya maraṇena sokehi paridevehi dukkhehi domanassehi upāyāsehi.**When these are not given up, you’re not freed from rebirth, old age, and death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[91]="*Na parimuccati dukkhasmāti vadāmi.**You’re not freed from suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[92]="*Saṃyojaniyesu, bhikkhave, dhammesu nibbidānupassī viharanto rāgaṃ pajahati, dosaṃ pajahati, mohaṃ pajahati.**When you keep seeing things that are prone to being fettered as boring, you give up greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[93]="*Rāgaṃ pahāya, dosaṃ pahāya, mohaṃ pahāya, parimuccati jātiyā jarāya maraṇena sokehi paridevehi dukkhehi domanassehi upāyāsehi.**When these are given up, you’re freed from rebirth, old age, and death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[94]="*Parimuccati dukkhasmāti vadāmi.**You’re freed from suffering, I say.*";
P_HTM[95]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve dhammā”ti.**These are the two things.”*";
P_HTM[96]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[97]="*7. Kaṇhasutta**7. Dark*";
P_HTM[98]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, dhammā kaṇhā.**“These two things, mendicants, are dark.*";
P_HTM[99]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[100]="*Ahirikañca anottappañca.**Lack of conscience and prudence.*";
P_HTM[101]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve dhammā kaṇhā”ti.**These are the two things that are dark.”*";
P_HTM[102]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[103]="*8. Sukkasutta**8. Bright*";
P_HTM[104]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, dhammā sukkā.**“These two things, mendicants, are bright.*";
P_HTM[105]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[106]="*Hirī ca ottappañca.**Conscience and prudence.*";
P_HTM[107]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve dhammā sukkā”ti.**These are the two things that are bright.”*";
P_HTM[108]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[109]="*9. Cariyasutta**9. Conduct*";
P_HTM[110]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, dhammā sukkā lokaṃ pālenti.**“These two bright things, mendicants, protect the world.*";
P_HTM[111]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[112]="*Hirī ca ottappañca.**Conscience and prudence.*";
P_HTM[113]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve sukkā dhammā lokaṃ na pāleyyuṃ, nayidha paññāyetha mātāti vā mātucchāti vā mātulānīti vā ācariyabhariyāti vā garūnaṃ dārāti vā.**If these two bright things did not protect the world, there would be no recognition of the status of mother, aunts, or wives and partners of teachers and respected people.*";
P_HTM[114]="*Sambhedaṃ loko agamissa, yathā ajeḷakā kukkuṭasūkarā soṇasiṅgālā.**The world would become promiscuous, like goats and sheep, chickens and pigs, and dogs and jackals.*";
P_HTM[115]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, ime dve sukkā dhammā lokaṃ pālenti tasmā paññāyati mātāti vā mātucchāti vā mātulānīti vā ācariyabhariyāti vā garūnaṃ dārāti vā”ti.**But because the two bright things protect the world, there is recognition of the status of mother, aunts, and wives and partners of teachers and respected people.”*";
P_HTM[116]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[117]="*10. Vassūpanāyikasutta**10. Entering the Rainy Season*";
P_HTM[118]="*“Dvemā, bhikkhave, vassūpanāyikā.**“There are, mendicants, these two entries to the rainy season.*";
P_HTM[119]="*Katamā dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[120]="*Purimikā ca pacchimikā ca.**Earlier and later.*";
P_HTM[121]="*Imā kho, bhikkhave, dve vassūpanāyikā”ti.**These are the two entries to the rainy season.”*";
P_HTM[122]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[123]="*Kammakaraṇavaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[124]="*Vajjā padhānā dve tapanīyā,* **";
P_HTM[125]="*Upaññātena pañcamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[126]="*Saṃyojanañca kaṇhañca,* **";
P_HTM[127]="*Sukkaṃ cariyā vassūpanāyikena vaggo.* **";
P_HTM[128]="*2. Padhānasuttaṃ**11*";
P_HTM[129]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, balāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two powers.*";
P_HTM[130]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[131]="*Paṭisaṅkhānabalañca bhāvanābalañca.**The power of reflection and the power of development.*";
P_HTM[132]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, paṭisaṅkhānabalaṃ?**And what, mendicants, is the power of reflection?*";
P_HTM[133]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco iti paṭisañcikkhati:**It’s when someone reflects:*";
P_HTM[134]="*‘kāyaduccaritassa kho pāpako vipāko diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca, vacīduccaritassa pāpako vipāko diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca, manoduccaritassa pāpako vipāko diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañcā’ti.**‘Bad conduct of body, speech, or mind has a bad, painful result in both this life and the next.’*";
P_HTM[135]="*So iti paṭisaṅkhāya kāyaduccaritaṃ pahāya kāyasucaritaṃ bhāveti, vacīduccaritaṃ pahāya vacīsucaritaṃ bhāveti, manoduccaritaṃ pahāya manosucaritaṃ bhāveti, suddhaṃ attānaṃ pariharati.**Reflecting like this, they give up bad conduct by way of body, speech, and mind, and develop good conduct by way of body, speech, and mind, keeping themselves pure.*";
P_HTM[136]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, paṭisaṅkhānabalaṃ.**This is called the power of reflection.*";
P_HTM[137]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, bhāvanābalaṃ.**And what, mendicants, is the power of development?*";
P_HTM[138]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yamidaṃ bhāvanābalaṃ sekhānametaṃ balaṃ.**In this context, the power of development is the power of the trainees.*";
P_HTM[139]="*Sekhañhi so, bhikkhave, balaṃ āgamma rāgaṃ pajahati, dosaṃ pajahati, mohaṃ pajahati.**For when you rely on the power of a trainee, you give up greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[140]="*Rāgaṃ pahāya, dosaṃ pahāya, mohaṃ pahāya yaṃ akusalaṃ na taṃ karoti, yaṃ pāpaṃ na taṃ sevati.**Then you don’t do anything unskillful, or practice anything bad.*";
P_HTM[141]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhāvanābalaṃ.**This is called the power of development.*";
P_HTM[142]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve balānī”ti.**These are the two powers.”*";
P_HTM[143]="*12**12*";
P_HTM[144]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, balāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two powers.*";
P_HTM[145]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[146]="*Paṭisaṅkhānabalañca bhāvanābalañca.**The power of reflection and the power of development.*";
P_HTM[147]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, paṭisaṅkhānabalaṃ?**And what, mendicants, is the power of reflection?*";
P_HTM[148]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco iti paṭisañcikkhati:**It’s when someone reflects:*";
P_HTM[149]="*‘kāyaduccaritassa kho pāpako vipāko diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca, vacīduccaritassa pāpako vipāko diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca, manoduccaritassa pāpako vipāko diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañcā’ti.**‘Bad conduct of body, speech, or mind has a bad, painful result in both this life and the next.’*";
P_HTM[150]="*So iti paṭisaṅkhāya kāyaduccaritaṃ pahāya kāyasucaritaṃ bhāveti, vacīduccaritaṃ pahāya vacīsucaritaṃ bhāveti, manoduccaritaṃ pahāya manosucaritaṃ bhāveti, suddhaṃ attānaṃ pariharati.**Reflecting like this, they give up bad conduct by way of body, speech, and mind, and develop good conduct by way of body, speech, and mind, keeping themselves pure.*";
P_HTM[151]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, paṭisaṅkhānabalaṃ.**This is called the power of reflection.*";
P_HTM[152]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, bhāvanābalaṃ?**And what, mendicants, is the power of development?*";
P_HTM[153]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vosaggapariṇāmiṃ, dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … vīriyasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pītisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … passaddhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … samādhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vosaggapariṇāmiṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[154]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhāvanābalaṃ.**This is called the power of development.*";
P_HTM[155]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve balānī”ti.**These are the two powers.”*";
P_HTM[156]="*13**13*";
P_HTM[157]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, balāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two powers.*";
P_HTM[158]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[159]="*Paṭisaṅkhānabalañca bhāvanābalañca.**The power of reflection and the power of development.*";
P_HTM[160]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, paṭisaṅkhānabalaṃ?**And what, mendicants, is the power of reflection?*";
P_HTM[161]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco iti paṭisañcikkhati:**It’s when someone reflects:*";
P_HTM[162]="*‘kāyaduccaritassa kho pāpako vipāko diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca, vacīduccaritassa kho pāpako vipāko diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca, manoduccaritassa kho pāpako vipāko diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañcā’ti.**‘Bad conduct of body, speech, or mind has a bad, painful result in both this life and the next.’*";
P_HTM[163]="*So iti paṭisaṅkhāya kāyaduccaritaṃ pahāya kāyasucaritaṃ bhāveti, vacīduccaritaṃ pahāya vacīsucaritaṃ bhāveti, manoduccaritaṃ pahāya manosucaritaṃ bhāveti, suddhaṃ attānaṃ pariharati.**Reflecting like this, they give up bad conduct by way of body, speech, and mind, and develop good conduct by way of body, speech, and mind, keeping themselves pure.*";
P_HTM[164]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, paṭisaṅkhānabalaṃ.**This is called the power of reflection.*";
P_HTM[165]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, bhāvanābalaṃ?**And what, mendicants, is the power of development?*";
P_HTM[166]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi, vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[167]="*Vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[168]="*Pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato ca sampajāno, sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti, yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**And with the fading away of rapture, they enter and remain in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[169]="*Sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[170]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, bhāvanābalaṃ.**This is called the power of development.*";
P_HTM[171]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve balānī”ti.**These are the two powers.”*";
P_HTM[172]="*14**14*";
P_HTM[173]="*“Dvemā, bhikkhave, tathāgatassa dhammadesanā.**“There are, mendicants, these two ways of teaching the Dhamma.*";
P_HTM[174]="*Katamā dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[175]="*Saṅkhittena ca vitthārena ca.**In brief and in detail.*";
P_HTM[176]="*Imā kho, bhikkhave, dve tathāgatassa dhammadesanā”ti.**These are two ways of teaching the Dhamma.”*";
P_HTM[177]="*15**15*";
P_HTM[178]="*“Yasmiṃ, bhikkhave, adhikaraṇe āpanno ca bhikkhu codako ca bhikkhu na sādhukaṃ attanāva attānaṃ paccavekkhati tasmetaṃ, bhikkhave, adhikaraṇe pāṭikaṅkhaṃ:**“Mendicants, in a disciplinary issue, if neither the offending mendicant nor the accusing mendicant carefully checks themselves, you can expect that issue*";
P_HTM[179]="*‘dīghattāya kharattāya vāḷattāya saṃvattissati, bhikkhū ca na phāsuṃ viharissantī’ti.**will lead to lasting acrimony and enmity, and the mendicants won’t live comfortably.*";
P_HTM[180]="*Yasmiñca kho, bhikkhave, adhikaraṇe āpanno ca bhikkhu codako ca bhikkhu sādhukaṃ attanāva attānaṃ paccavekkhati tasmetaṃ, bhikkhave, adhikaraṇe pāṭikaṅkhaṃ:**But in a disciplinary issue, if both the offending mendicant and the accusing mendicant carefully check themselves, you can expect that issue*";
P_HTM[181]="*‘na dīghattāya kharattāya vāḷattāya saṃvattissati, bhikkhū ca phāsuṃ viharissantī’ti.**won’t lead to lasting acrimony and enmity, and the mendicants will live comfortably.*";
P_HTM[182]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, āpanno bhikkhu sādhukaṃ attanāva attānaṃ paccavekkhati?**And how, mendicants, does an offending mendicant carefully check themselves?*";
P_HTM[183]="*Idha, bhikkhave, āpanno bhikkhu iti paṭisañcikkhati:**An offending mendicant reflects:*";
P_HTM[184]="*‘ahaṃ kho akusalaṃ āpanno kañcideva desaṃ kāyena.**‘I have committed a certain unskillful offense with the body.*";
P_HTM[185]="*Maṃ so bhikkhu addasa akusalaṃ āpajjamānaṃ kañcideva desaṃ kāyena.**That mendicant saw me do this.*";
P_HTM[186]="*No ce ahaṃ akusalaṃ āpajjeyyaṃ kañcideva desaṃ kāyena, na maṃ so bhikkhu passeyya akusalaṃ āpajjamānaṃ kañcideva desaṃ kāyena.**If I hadn’t committed that offense, they wouldn’t have seen me.*";
P_HTM[187]="*Yasmā ca kho, ahaṃ akusalaṃ āpanno kañcideva desaṃ kāyena, tasmā maṃ so bhikkhu addasa akusalaṃ āpajjamānaṃ kañcideva desaṃ kāyena.**But since I did commit that offense, they did see me.*";
P_HTM[188]="*Disvā ca pana maṃ so bhikkhu akusalaṃ āpajjamānaṃ kañcideva desaṃ kāyena anattamano ahosi.**When they saw me, they were upset,*";
P_HTM[189]="*Anattamano samāno anattamanavacanaṃ maṃ so bhikkhu avaca.**and they voiced their unhappiness to me.*";
P_HTM[190]="*Anattamanavacanāhaṃ tena bhikkhunā vutto samāno anattamano ahosiṃ.**Then I also got upset,*";
P_HTM[191]="*Anattamano samāno paresaṃ ārocesiṃ.**so I told others.*";
P_HTM[192]="*Iti mameva tattha accayo accagamā suṅkadāyakaṃva bhaṇḍasmin’ti.**So the mistake is mine alone, like someone who owes customs duty on their goods.’*";
P_HTM[193]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, āpanno bhikkhu sādhukaṃ attanāva attānaṃ paccavekkhati.**That’s how, mendicants, an offending mendicant carefully checks themselves.*";
P_HTM[194]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, codako bhikkhu sādhukaṃ attanāva attānaṃ paccavekkhati?**And how, mendicants, does an accusing mendicant carefully check themselves?*";
P_HTM[195]="*Idha, bhikkhave, codako bhikkhu iti paṭisañcikkhati:**An accusing mendicant reflects:*";
P_HTM[196]="*‘ayaṃ kho bhikkhu akusalaṃ āpanno kañcideva desaṃ kāyena.**‘This mendicant has committed a certain unskillful offense with the body.*";
P_HTM[197]="*Ahaṃ imaṃ bhikkhuṃ addasaṃ akusalaṃ āpajjamānaṃ kañcideva desaṃ kāyena.**I saw them do that.*";
P_HTM[198]="*No ce ayaṃ bhikkhu akusalaṃ āpajjeyya kañcideva desaṃ kāyena, nāhaṃ imaṃ bhikkhuṃ passeyyaṃ akusalaṃ āpajjamānaṃ kañcideva desaṃ kāyena.**If they hadn’t committed that offense, I wouldn’t have seen them.*";
P_HTM[199]="*Yasmā ca kho, ayaṃ bhikkhu akusalaṃ āpanno kañcideva desaṃ kāyena, tasmā ahaṃ imaṃ bhikkhuṃ addasaṃ akusalaṃ āpajjamānaṃ kañcideva desaṃ kāyena.**But since they did commit that offense, I did see them.*";
P_HTM[200]="*Disvā ca panāhaṃ imaṃ bhikkhuṃ akusalaṃ āpajjamānaṃ kañcideva desaṃ kāyena anattamano ahosiṃ.**When I saw them, I was upset,*";
P_HTM[201]="*Anattamano samāno anattamanavacanāhaṃ imaṃ bhikkhuṃ avacaṃ.**and I voiced my unhappiness to them.*";
P_HTM[202]="*Anattamanavacanāyaṃ bhikkhu mayā vutto samāno anattamano ahosi.**Then they also got upset,*";
P_HTM[203]="*Anattamano samāno paresaṃ ārocesi.**so they told others.*";
P_HTM[204]="*Iti mameva tattha accayo accagamā suṅkadāyakaṃva bhaṇḍasmin’ti.**So the mistake is mine alone, like someone who owes customs duty on their goods.’*";
P_HTM[205]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, codako bhikkhu sādhukaṃ attanāva attānaṃ paccavekkhati.**That’s how, mendicants, an accusing mendicant carefully checks themselves.*";
P_HTM[206]="*Yasmiṃ, bhikkhave, adhikaraṇe āpanno ca bhikkhu codako ca bhikkhu na sādhukaṃ attanāva attānaṃ paccavekkhati tasmetaṃ, bhikkhave, adhikaraṇe pāṭikaṅkhaṃ dīghattāya kharattāya vāḷattāya saṃvattissati, bhikkhū ca na phāsuṃ viharissantīti.**In a disciplinary issue, if neither the offending mendicant nor the accusing mendicant carefully checks themselves, you can expect that issue will lead to lasting acrimony and enmity, and the mendicants won’t live comfortably.*";
P_HTM[207]="*Yasmiñca kho, bhikkhave, adhikaraṇe āpanno ca bhikkhu codako ca bhikkhu sādhukaṃ attanāva attānaṃ paccavekkhati tasmetaṃ, bhikkhave, adhikaraṇe pāṭikaṅkhaṃ na dīghattāya kharattāya vāḷattāya saṃvattissati, bhikkhū ca phāsuṃ viharissantī”ti.**But in a disciplinary issue, if both the offending mendicant and the accusing mendicant carefully checks themselves, you can expect that issue won’t lead to lasting acrimony and enmity, and the mendicants will live comfortably.”*";
P_HTM[208]="*16**16*";
P_HTM[209]="*Atha kho aññataro brāhmaṇo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then a certain brahmin went up to the Buddha and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[210]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[211]="*“ko nu kho, bho gotama, hetu ko paccayo yena m’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjantī”ti?**“What is the cause, Master Gotama, what is the reason why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell?”*";
P_HTM[212]="*“Adhammacariyāvisamacariyāhetu kho, brāhmaṇa, evam’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjantī”ti.**“Unprincipled and immoral conduct is the reason why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.”*";
P_HTM[213]="*“Ko nu kho, bho gotama, hetu ko paccayo yena m’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjantī”ti?**“What is the cause, Master Gotama, what is the reason why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm?”*";
P_HTM[214]="*“Dhammacariyāsamacariyāhetu kho, brāhmaṇa, evam’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjantī”ti.**“Principled and moral conduct is the reason why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.”*";
P_HTM[215]="*“Abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama, abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama.**“Excellent, Master Gotama! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[216]="*Seyyathāpi, bho gotama, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhotā gotamena anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he was righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, Master Gotama has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[217]="*Esāhaṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṃghañca.**I go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[218]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ gotamo dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may Master Gotama remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[219]="*17**17*";
P_HTM[220]="*Atha kho jāṇussoṇi brāhmaṇo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then the brahmin Jāṇussoṇi went up to the Buddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[221]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho jāṇussoṇi brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[222]="*“ko nu kho, bho gotama, hetu ko paccayo yena m’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjantī”ti?**“What is the cause, Master Gotama, what is the reason why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell?”*";
P_HTM[223]="*“Katattā ca, brāhmaṇa, akatattā ca.**“What they’ve done and what they’ve not done.*";
P_HTM[224]="*Evam’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjantī”ti.**That’s why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.”*";
P_HTM[225]="*“Ko pana, bho gotama, hetu ko paccayo yena m’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjantī”ti?**“But what is the cause, Master Gotama, what is the reason why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm?”*";
P_HTM[226]="*“Katattā ca, brāhmaṇa, akatattā ca.**“What they’ve done and what they’ve not done.*";
P_HTM[227]="*Evam’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjantī”ti.**That’s why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.”*";
P_HTM[228]="*“Na kho ahaṃ imassa bhoto gotamassa saṃkhittena bhāsitassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ ājānāmi.**“I don’t understand the meaning of what Master Gotama has said in brief, without explaining the details.*";
P_HTM[229]="*Sādhu me bhavaṃ gotamo tathā dhammaṃ desetu yathā ahaṃ imassa bhoto gotamassa saṃkhittena bhāsitassa vitthārena atthaṃ avibhattassa vitthārena atthaṃ ājāneyyan”ti.**Master Gotama, please teach me this matter in detail so I can understand the meaning.”*";
P_HTM[230]="*“Tena hi, brāhmaṇa, suṇāhi, sādhukaṃ manasi karohi; bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, brahmin, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[231]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho jāṇussoṇi brāhmaṇo bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes sir,” Jāṇussoṇi replied.*";
P_HTM[232]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[233]="*“Idha, brāhmaṇa, ekaccassa kāyaduccaritaṃ kataṃ hoti, akataṃ hoti kāyasucaritaṃ;**“Firstly, brahmin, someone has done bad things and not done good things by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[234]="*vacīduccaritaṃ kataṃ hoti, akataṃ hoti vacīsucaritaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[235]="*manoduccaritaṃ kataṃ hoti, akataṃ hoti manosucaritaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[236]="*Evaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, katattā ca akatattā ca evam’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjanti.**So what they’ve done and what they’ve not done is why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[237]="*Idha pana, brāhmaṇa, ekaccassa kāyasucaritaṃ kataṃ hoti, akataṃ hoti kāyaduccaritaṃ;**Furthermore, brahmin, someone has done good things and not done bad things by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[238]="*vacīsucaritaṃ kataṃ hoti, akataṃ hoti vacīduccaritaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[239]="*manosucaritaṃ kataṃ hoti, akataṃ hoti manoduccaritaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[240]="*Evaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, katattā ca akatattā ca evam’idhekacce sattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjantī”ti.**So what they’ve done and what they’ve not done is why some sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.”*";
P_HTM[241]="*“Abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama … pe … upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ gotamo dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**“Excellent, Master Gotama! … From this day forth, may Master Gotama remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[242]="*18**18*";
P_HTM[243]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[244]="*“ekaṃsenāhaṃ, ānanda, akaraṇīyaṃ vadāmi kāyaduccaritaṃ vacīduccaritaṃ manoduccaritan”ti.**“Ānanda, I absolutely say that you should not do bad things by way of body, speech, and mind.”*";
P_HTM[245]="*“Yamidaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā ekaṃsena akaraṇīyaṃ akkhātaṃ kāyaduccaritaṃ vacīduccaritaṃ manoduccaritaṃ tasmiṃ akaraṇīye kayiramāne ko ādīnavo pāṭikaṅkho”ti?**“But, sir, if someone does these things that should not be done, what drawbacks should they expect?”*";
P_HTM[246]="*“Yamidaṃ, ānanda, mayā ekaṃsena akaraṇīyaṃ akkhātaṃ kāyaduccaritaṃ vacīduccaritaṃ manoduccaritaṃ tasmiṃ akaraṇīye kayiramāne ayaṃ ādīnavo pāṭikaṅkho—**“They should expect these drawbacks.*";
P_HTM[247]="*attāpi attānaṃ upavadati,**They blame themselves.*";
P_HTM[248]="*anuvicca viññū garahanti,**After examination, sensible people criticize them.*";
P_HTM[249]="*pāpako kittisaddo abbhuggacchati,**They get a bad reputation.*";
P_HTM[250]="*sammūḷho kālaṃ karoti,**They feel lost when they die.*";
P_HTM[251]="*kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**And when their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[252]="*Yamidaṃ, ānanda, mayā ekaṃsena akaraṇīyaṃ akkhātaṃ kāyaduccaritaṃ vacīduccaritaṃ manoduccaritaṃ tasmiṃ akaraṇīye kayiramāne ayaṃ ādīnavo pāṭikaṅkho”ti.**These are the drawbacks they should expect.”*";
P_HTM[253]="*“Ekaṃsenāhaṃ, ānanda, karaṇīyaṃ vadāmi kāyasucaritaṃ vacīsucaritaṃ manosucaritan”ti.**“Ānanda, I absolutely say that you should do good things by way of body, speech, and mind.”*";
P_HTM[254]="*“Yamidaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā ekaṃsena karaṇīyaṃ akkhātaṃ kāyasucaritaṃ vacīsucaritaṃ manosucaritaṃ tasmiṃ karaṇīye kayiramāne ko ānisaṃso pāṭikaṅkho”ti?**“But, sir, if someone does these things that should be done, what benefits should they expect?”*";
P_HTM[255]="*“Yamidaṃ, ānanda, mayā ekaṃsena karaṇīyaṃ akkhātaṃ kāyasucaritaṃ vacīsucaritaṃ manosucaritaṃ tasmiṃ karaṇīye kayiramāne ayaṃ ānisaṃso pāṭikaṅkho—**“They should expect these benefits.*";
P_HTM[256]="*attāpi attānaṃ na upavadati,**They don’t blame themselves.*";
P_HTM[257]="*anuvicca viññū pasaṃsanti,**After examination, sensible people praise them.*";
P_HTM[258]="*kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggacchati,**They get a good reputation.*";
P_HTM[259]="*asammūḷho kālaṃ karoti,**They don’t feel lost when they die.*";
P_HTM[260]="*kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**And when the body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[261]="*Yamidaṃ, ānanda, mayā ekaṃsena karaṇīyaṃ akkhātaṃ kāyasucaritaṃ vacīsucaritaṃ manosucaritaṃ tasmiṃ karaṇīye kayiramāne ayaṃ ānisaṃso pāṭikaṅkho”ti.**These are the benefits they should expect.”*";
P_HTM[262]="*19**19*";
P_HTM[263]="*“Akusalaṃ, bhikkhave, pajahatha.**“Mendicants, give up the unskillful.*";
P_HTM[264]="*Sakkā, bhikkhave, akusalaṃ pajahituṃ.**It is possible to give up the unskillful.*";
P_HTM[265]="*No cedaṃ, bhikkhave, sakkā abhavissa akusalaṃ pajahituṃ, nāhaṃ evaṃ vadeyyaṃ:**If it wasn’t possible, I wouldn’t say:*";
P_HTM[266]="*‘akusalaṃ, bhikkhave, pajahathā’ti.**‘Give up the unskillful.’*";
P_HTM[267]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, sakkā akusalaṃ pajahituṃ tasmāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**But it is possible, and so I say:*";
P_HTM[268]="*‘akusalaṃ, bhikkhave, pajahathā’ti.**‘Give up the unskillful.’*";
P_HTM[269]="*Akusalañca hidaṃ, bhikkhave, pahīnaṃ ahitāya dukkhāya saṃvatteyya nāhaṃ evaṃ vadeyyaṃ:**And if giving up the unskillful led to harm and suffering, I would not say:*";
P_HTM[270]="*‘akusalaṃ, bhikkhave, pajahathā’ti.**‘Give up the unskillful.’*";
P_HTM[271]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, akusalaṃ pahīnaṃ hitāya sukhāya saṃvattati tasmāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**But giving up the unskillful leads to welfare and happiness, so I say:*";
P_HTM[272]="*‘akusalaṃ, bhikkhave, pajahathā’”ti.**‘Give up the unskillful.’*";
P_HTM[273]="*“Kusalaṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvetha.**Mendicants, develop the skillful.*";
P_HTM[274]="*Sakkā, bhikkhave, kusalaṃ bhāvetuṃ.**It is possible to develop the skillful.*";
P_HTM[275]="*No cedaṃ, bhikkhave, sakkā abhavissa kusalaṃ bhāvetuṃ, nāhaṃ evaṃ vadeyyaṃ:**If it wasn’t possible, I wouldn’t say:*";
P_HTM[276]="*‘kusalaṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvethā’ti.**‘Develop the skillful.’*";
P_HTM[277]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, sakkā kusalaṃ bhāvetuṃ tasmāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**But it is possible, and so I say:*";
P_HTM[278]="*‘kusalaṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvethā’ti.**‘Develop the skillful.’*";
P_HTM[279]="*Kusalañca hidaṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvitaṃ ahitāya dukkhāya saṃvatteyya, nāhaṃ evaṃ vadeyyaṃ:**If developing the skillful led to harm and suffering I wouldn’t say:*";
P_HTM[280]="*‘kusalaṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvethā’ti.**‘Develop the skillful.’*";
P_HTM[281]="*Yasmā ca kho, bhikkhave, kusalaṃ bhāvitaṃ hitāya sukhāya saṃvattati tasmāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**But developing the skillful leads to welfare and happiness, so I say:*";
P_HTM[282]="*‘kusalaṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvethā’”ti.**‘Develop the skillful.’”*";
P_HTM[283]="*20**20*";
P_HTM[284]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, dhammā saddhammassa sammosāya antaradhānāya saṃvattanti.**“These two things, mendicants, lead to the decline and disappearance of the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[285]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[286]="*Dunnikkhittañca padabyañjanaṃ attho ca dunnīto.**The words and phrases are misplaced, and the meaning is misinterpreted.*";
P_HTM[287]="*Dunnikkhittassa, bhikkhave, padabyañjanassa atthopi dunnayo hoti.**When the words and phrases are misplaced, the meaning is misinterpreted.*";
P_HTM[288]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve dhammā saddhammassa sammosāya antaradhānāya saṃvattantī”ti.**These two things lead to the decline and disappearance of the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[289]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, dhammā saddhammassa ṭhitiyā asammosāya anantaradhānāya saṃvattanti.**These two things lead to the continuation, persistence, and enduring of the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[290]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[291]="*Sunikkhittañca padabyañjanaṃ attho ca sunīto.**The words and phrases are well organized, and the meaning is correctly interpreted.*";
P_HTM[292]="*Sunikkhittassa, bhikkhave, padabyañjanassa atthopi sunayo hoti.**When the words and phrases are well organized, the meaning is correctly interpreted.*";
P_HTM[293]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve dhammā saddhammassa ṭhitiyā asammosāya anantaradhānāya saṃvattantī”ti.**These two things lead to the continuation, persistence, and enduring of the true teaching.”*";
P_HTM[294]="*Adhikaraṇavaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[295]="*3. Tapanīyasuttaṃ**21*";
P_HTM[296]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, bālā.**“Mendicants, there are two fools.*";
P_HTM[297]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[298]="*Yo ca accayaṃ accayato na passati, yo ca accayaṃ desentassa yathādhammaṃ nappaṭiggaṇhāti.**One who doesn’t recognize when they’ve made a mistake. And one who doesn’t properly accept the confession of someone who’s made a mistake.*";
P_HTM[299]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve bālāti.**These are the two fools.*";
P_HTM[300]="*Dveme, bhikkhave, paṇḍitā.**There are two who are astute.*";
P_HTM[301]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[302]="*Yo ca accayaṃ accayato passati, yo ca accayaṃ desentassa yathādhammaṃ paṭiggaṇhāti.**One who recognizes when they’ve made a mistake. And one who properly accepts the confession of someone who’s made a mistake.*";
P_HTM[303]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve paṇḍitā”ti.**These are the two who are astute.”*";
P_HTM[304]="*22**22*";
P_HTM[305]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, tathāgataṃ abbhācikkhanti.**“Mendicants, these two misrepresent the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[306]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[307]="*Duṭṭho vā dosantaro, saddho vā duggahitena.**One who is hateful and hides it, and one whose faith is mistaken.*";
P_HTM[308]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve tathāgataṃ abbhācikkhantī”ti.**These two misrepresent the Realized One.”*";
P_HTM[309]="*23**23*";
P_HTM[310]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, tathāgataṃ abbhācikkhanti.**“Mendicants, these two misrepresent the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[311]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[312]="*Yo ca abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatena bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpeti, yo ca bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatena abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpeti.**One who explains what was not spoken by the Realized One as spoken by him. And one who explains what was spoken by the Realized One as not spoken by him.*";
P_HTM[313]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve tathāgataṃ abbhācikkhantīti.**These two misrepresent the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[314]="*Dveme, bhikkhave, tathāgataṃ nābbhācikkhanti.**These two don’t misrepresent the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[315]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[316]="*Yo ca abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatena abhāsitaṃ alapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpeti, yo ca bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatena bhāsitaṃ lapitaṃ tathāgatenāti dīpeti.**One who explains what was not spoken by the Realized One as not spoken by him. And one who explains what was spoken by the Realized One as spoken by him.*";
P_HTM[317]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve tathāgataṃ nābbhācikkhantī”ti.**These two don’t misrepresent the Realized One.”*";
P_HTM[318]="*24**24*";
P_HTM[319]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, tathāgataṃ abbhācikkhanti.**“Mendicants, these two misrepresent the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[320]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[321]="*Yo ca neyyatthaṃ suttantaṃ nītattho suttantoti dīpeti, yo ca nītatthaṃ suttantaṃ neyyattho suttantoti dīpeti.**One who explains a discourse in need of interpretation as a discourse whose meaning is explicit. And one who explains a discourse whose meaning is explicit as a discourse in need of interpretation.*";
P_HTM[322]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve tathāgataṃ abbhācikkhantī”ti.**These two misrepresent the Realized One.”*";
P_HTM[323]="*25**25*";
P_HTM[324]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, tathāgataṃ nābbhācikkhanti.**“These two don’t misrepresent the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[325]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[326]="*Yo ca neyyatthaṃ suttantaṃ neyyattho suttantoti dīpeti, yo ca nītatthaṃ suttantaṃ nītattho suttantoti dīpeti.**One who explains a discourse in need of interpretation as a discourse in need of interpretation. And one who explains a discourse whose meaning is explicit as a discourse whose meaning is explicit.*";
P_HTM[327]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve tathāgataṃ nābbhācikkhantī”ti.**These two don’t misrepresent the Realized One.”*";
P_HTM[328]="*26**26*";
P_HTM[329]="*“Paṭicchannakammantassa, bhikkhave, dvinnaṃ gatīnaṃ aññatarā gati pāṭikaṅkhā—**“Mendicants, when you hide your misdeeds, you can expect one of two destinies:*";
P_HTM[330]="*nirayo vā tiracchānayoni vāti.**hell or the animal realm.*";
P_HTM[331]="*Appaṭicchannakammantassa, bhikkhave, dvinnaṃ gatīnaṃ aññatarā gati pāṭikaṅkhā—**When you don’t hide your misdeeds, you can expect one of two destinies:*";
P_HTM[332]="*devā vā manussā vā”ti.**as a god or a human.”*";
P_HTM[333]="*27**27*";
P_HTM[334]="*“Micchādiṭṭhikassa, bhikkhave, dvinnaṃ gatīnaṃ aññatarā gati pāṭikaṅkhā—**“Mendicants, when you have wrong view, you can expect one of two destinies:*";
P_HTM[335]="*nirayo vā tiracchānayoni vā”ti.**hell or the animal realm.”*";
P_HTM[336]="*28**28*";
P_HTM[337]="*“Sammādiṭṭhikassa, bhikkhave, dvinnaṃ gatīnaṃ aññatarā gati pāṭikaṅkhā—**“Mendicants, when you have right view, you can expect one of two destinies:*";
P_HTM[338]="*devā vā manussā vā”ti.**as a god or a human.”*";
P_HTM[339]="*29**29*";
P_HTM[340]="*“Dussīlassa, bhikkhave, dve paṭiggāhā—**“There are two places waiting to receive an unethical person:*";
P_HTM[341]="*nirayo vā tiracchānayoni vā.**hell and the animal realm.*";
P_HTM[342]="*Sīlavato, bhikkhave, dve paṭiggāhā—**There are two places waiting to receive an ethical person:*";
P_HTM[343]="*devā vā manussā vā”ti.**the realms of gods and humans.”*";
P_HTM[344]="*30**30*";
P_HTM[345]="*“Dvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, atthavase sampassamāno araññavanapatthāni pantāni senāsanāni paṭisevāmi.**“Mendicants, I see two reasons to frequent remote lodgings in the wilderness and the forest.*";
P_HTM[346]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[347]="*Attano ca diṭṭhadhammasukhavihāraṃ sampassamāno, pacchimañca janataṃ anukampamāno.**Seeing a happy life for oneself in the present, and having compassion for future generations.*";
P_HTM[348]="*Ime kho ahaṃ, bhikkhave, dve atthavase sampassamāno araññavanapatthāni pantāni senāsanāni paṭisevāmī”ti.**I see two reasons to frequent remote lodgings in the wilderness and the forest.”*";
P_HTM[349]="*31**31*";
P_HTM[350]="*“Dve me, bhikkhave, dhammā vijjābhāgiyā.**“These two things play a part in realization.*";
P_HTM[351]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[352]="*Samatho ca vipassanā ca.**Serenity and discernment.*";
P_HTM[353]="*Samatho, bhikkhave, bhāvito kamatthamanubhoti?**What is the benefit of developing serenity?*";
P_HTM[354]="*Cittaṃ bhāvīyati.**The mind is developed.*";
P_HTM[355]="*Cittaṃ bhāvitaṃ kamatthamanubhoti?**What is the benefit of developing the mind?*";
P_HTM[356]="*Yo rāgo so pahīyati.**Greed is given up.*";
P_HTM[357]="*Vipassanā, bhikkhave, bhāvitā kamatthamanubhoti?**What is the benefit of developing discernment?*";
P_HTM[358]="*Paññā bhāvīyati.**Wisdom is developed.*";
P_HTM[359]="*Paññā bhāvitā kamatthamanubhoti?**What is the benefit of developing wisdom?*";
P_HTM[360]="*Yā avijjā sā pahīyati.**Ignorance is given up.*";
P_HTM[361]="*Rāgupakkiliṭṭhaṃ vā, bhikkhave, cittaṃ na vimuccati, avijjupakkiliṭṭhā vā paññā na bhāvīyati.**The mind contaminated by greed is not free; and wisdom contaminated by ignorance does not grow.*";
P_HTM[362]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, rāgavirāgā cetovimutti, avijjāvirāgā paññāvimuttī”ti.**In this way, freedom of heart comes from the fading away of greed, while freedom by wisdom comes from the fading away of ignorance.”*";
P_HTM[363]="*Bālavaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[364]="*4. Atapanīyasuttaṃ**32*";
P_HTM[365]="*“Asappurisabhūmiñca vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi sappurisabhūmiñca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you the level of the bad person and the level of the good person.*";
P_HTM[366]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha. bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[367]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[368]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[369]="*“Katamā ca, bhikkhave, asappurisabhūmi?**“What is the level of the bad person?*";
P_HTM[370]="*Asappuriso, bhikkhave, akataññū hoti akatavedī.**The bad person is ungrateful and thankless,*";
P_HTM[371]="*Asabbhi hetaṃ, bhikkhave, upaññātaṃ yadidaṃ akataññutā akataveditā.**for the wicked only know how to be ungrateful and thankless.*";
P_HTM[372]="*Kevalā esā, bhikkhave, asappurisabhūmi yadidaṃ akataññutā akataveditā. ()**It is totally the level of a bad person to be ungrateful and thankless.*";
P_HTM[373]="*Sappuriso ca kho, bhikkhave, kataññū hoti katavedī.**The good person is grateful and thankful,*";
P_HTM[374]="*Sabbhi hetaṃ, bhikkhave, upaññātaṃ yadidaṃ kataññutā kataveditā.**for the virtuous only know how to be grateful and thankful.*";
P_HTM[375]="*Kevalā esā, bhikkhave, sappurisabhūmi yadidaṃ kataññutā kataveditā”ti.**It is totally the level of a good person to be grateful and thankful.”*";
P_HTM[376]="*33**33*";
P_HTM[377]="*“Dvinnāhaṃ, bhikkhave, na suppatikāraṃ vadāmi.**“Mendicants, I say that these two people cannot easily be repaid.*";
P_HTM[378]="*Katamesaṃ dvinnaṃ?**What two?*";
P_HTM[379]="*Mātu ca pitu ca.**Mother and father.*";
P_HTM[380]="*Ekena, bhikkhave, aṃsena mātaraṃ parihareyya, ekena aṃsena pitaraṃ parihareyya vassasatāyuko vassasatajīvī so ca nesaṃ ucchādanaparimaddananhāpanasambāhanena.**You would not have done enough to repay your mother and father even if you were to carry your mother around on one shoulder, and your father on the other, and if you lived like this for a hundred years, and if you were to anoint, massage, bathe, and rub them;*";
P_HTM[381]="*Te ca tattheva muttakarīsaṃ cajeyyuṃ, na tveva, bhikkhave, mātāpitūnaṃ kataṃ vā hoti paṭikataṃ vā.**and even if they were to defecate and urinate right there.*";
P_HTM[382]="*Imissā ca, bhikkhave, mahāpathaviyā pahūtarattaratanāya mātāpitaro issarādhipacce rajje patiṭṭhāpeyya, na tveva, bhikkhave, mātāpitūnaṃ kataṃ vā hoti paṭikataṃ vā.**Even if you were to establish your mother and father as supreme monarchs of this great earth, abounding in the seven treasures, you would still not have done enough to repay them.*";
P_HTM[383]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[384]="*Bahukārā, bhikkhave, mātāpitaro puttānaṃ āpādakā posakā imassa lokassa dassetāro.**Parents are very helpful to their children, they raise them, nurture them, and show them the world.*";
P_HTM[385]="*Yo ca kho, bhikkhave, mātāpitaro assaddhe saddhāsampadāya samādapeti niveseti patiṭṭhāpeti, dussīle sīlasampadāya samādapeti niveseti patiṭṭhāpeti, maccharī cāgasampadāya samādapeti niveseti patiṭṭhāpeti, duppaññe paññāsampadāya samādapeti niveseti patiṭṭhāpeti, ettāvatā kho, bhikkhave, mātāpitūnaṃ katañca hoti paṭikatañcā”ti.**But you have done enough, more than enough, to repay them if you encourage, settle, and ground unfaithful parents in faith, unethical parents in ethical conduct, stingy parents in generosity, or ignorant parents in wisdom.”*";
P_HTM[386]="*34**34*";
P_HTM[387]="*Atha kho aññataro brāhmaṇo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi. Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a certain brahmin went up to the Buddha, and exchanged greetings with him. When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[388]="*“kiṃvādī bhavaṃ gotamo kimakkhāyī”ti?**“What does Master Gotama teach? What does he explain?”*";
P_HTM[389]="*“Kiriyavādī cāhaṃ, brāhmaṇa, akiriyavādī cā”ti.**“Brahmin, I teach action and inaction.”*";
P_HTM[390]="*“Yathākathaṃ pana bhavaṃ gotamo kiriyavādī ca akiriyavādī cā”ti?**“But in what way does Master Gotama teach action and inaction?”*";
P_HTM[391]="*“Akiriyaṃ kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, vadāmi kāyaduccaritassa vacīduccaritassa manoduccaritassa, anekavihitānaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ akiriyaṃ vadāmi.**“I teach inaction regarding bad bodily, verbal, and mental conduct, and the many kinds of unskillful things.*";
P_HTM[392]="*Kiriyañca kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, vadāmi kāyasucaritassa vacīsucaritassa manosucaritassa, anekavihitānaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ kiriyaṃ vadāmi.**I teach action regarding good bodily, verbal, and mental conduct, and the many kinds of skillful things.*";
P_HTM[393]="*Evaṃ kho ahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, kiriyavādī ca akiriyavādī cā”ti.**This is the kind of action and inaction that I teach.”*";
P_HTM[394]="*“Abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama … pe … upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ gotamo dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**“Excellent, Master Gotama! … From this day forth, may Master Gotama remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[395]="*35**35*";
P_HTM[396]="*Atha kho anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then the householder Anāthapiṇḍika went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[397]="*“kati nu kho, bhante, loke dakkhiṇeyyā, kattha ca dānaṃ dātabban”ti?**“How many kinds of people in the world are worthy of a religious donation? And where should a gift be given?”*";
P_HTM[398]="*“Dve kho, gahapati, loke dakkhiṇeyyā—**“Householder, there are two kinds of people in the world who are worthy of a religious donation:*";
P_HTM[399]="*sekho ca asekho ca.**the trainee and the master.*";
P_HTM[400]="*Ime kho, gahapati, dve loke dakkhiṇeyyā, ettha ca dānaṃ dātabban”ti.**These are two kinds of people in the world who are worthy of a religious donation, and that’s where you should give a gift.”*";
P_HTM[401]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[402]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[403]="*“Sekho asekho ca imasmiṃ loke,**“In this world, the trainee and the master,*";
P_HTM[404]="*Āhuneyyā yajamānānaṃ honti;**are worthy of the offerings of those who sponsor sacrifices.*";
P_HTM[405]="*Te ujjubhūtā kāyena,**They are upright in body,*";
P_HTM[406]="*Vācāya uda cetasā;**speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[407]="*Khettaṃ taṃ yajamānānaṃ,**This is the field for sponsors of sacrifice—*";
P_HTM[408]="*Ettha dinnaṃ mahapphalan”ti.**what’s given here is very fruitful.”*";
P_HTM[409]="*36**36*";
P_HTM[410]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[411]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[412]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā sāriputto sāvatthiyaṃ viharati pubbārāme migāramātupāsāde.**Now at that time Venerable Sāriputta was staying near Sāvatthī in the Eastern Monastery, the stilt longhouse of Migāra’s mother.*";
P_HTM[413]="*Tatra kho āyasmā sāriputto bhikkhū āmantesi:**There Sāriputta addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[414]="*“āvuso bhikkhave”ti.**“Reverends, mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[415]="*“Āvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa paccassosuṃ.**“Reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[416]="*Āyasmā sāriputto etadavoca:**Sāriputta said this:*";
P_HTM[417]="*“ajjhattasaṃyojanañca, āvuso, puggalaṃ desessāmi bahiddhāsaṃyojanañca.**“I will teach you about a person fettered internally and one fettered externally.*";
P_HTM[418]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[419]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[420]="*Āyasmā sāriputto etadavoca:**Sāriputta said this:*";
P_HTM[421]="*“Katamo cāvuso, ajjhattasaṃyojano puggalo?**“Who is a person fettered internally?*";
P_HTM[422]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno, aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu.**It’s a mendicant who is ethical, restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[423]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā aññataraṃ devanikāyaṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in one of the orders of gods.*";
P_HTM[424]="*So tato cuto āgāmī hoti, āgantā itthattaṃ.**When they pass away from there, they’re a returner, who comes back to this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[425]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, āvuso, ajjhattasaṃyojano puggalo āgāmī hoti, āgantā itthattaṃ.**This is called a person who is fettered internally, a returner, who comes back to this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[426]="*Katamo cāvuso, bahiddhāsaṃyojano puggalo?**Who is a person fettered externally?*";
P_HTM[427]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno, aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu.**It’s a mendicant who is ethical, restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[428]="*So aññataraṃ santaṃ cetovimuttiṃ upasampajja viharati.**They enter and remain in a certain peaceful state of freed mind.*";
P_HTM[429]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā aññataraṃ devanikāyaṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in one of the orders of gods.*";
P_HTM[430]="*So tato cuto anāgāmī hoti, anāgantā itthattaṃ.**When they pass away from there, they’re a non-returner, not coming back to this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[431]="*Ayaṃ vuccatāvuso, bahiddhāsaṃyojano puggalo anāgāmī hoti, anāgantā itthattaṃ.**This is called a person who is fettered externally, a non-returner, who does not come back to this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[432]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti … pe … samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu.**Furthermore, a mendicant is ethical … they keep the rules they’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[433]="*So kāmānaṃyeva nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti.**They simply practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[434]="*So bhavānaṃyeva nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya paṭipanno hoti.**They simply practice for disillusionment, dispassion, and cessation regarding future lives.*";
P_HTM[435]="*So taṇhākkhayāya paṭipanno hoti.**They practice for the ending of craving.*";
P_HTM[436]="*So lobhakkhayāya paṭipanno hoti.**They practice for the ending of greed.*";
P_HTM[437]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā aññataraṃ devanikāyaṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in one of the orders of gods.*";
P_HTM[438]="*So tato cuto anāgāmī hoti, anāgantā itthattaṃ.**When they pass away from there, they are non-returners, not coming back to this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[439]="*Ayaṃ vuccatāvuso, bahiddhāsaṃyojano puggalo anāgāmī hoti, anāgantā itthattan”ti.**This is called a person who is fettered externally, a non-returner, who does not come back to this state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[440]="*Atha kho sambahulā samacittā devatā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho tā devatā bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several peaceful-minded deities went up to the Buddha, bowed, stood to one side, and said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[441]="*“eso, bhante, āyasmā sāriputto pubbārāme migāramātupāsāde bhikkhūnaṃ ajjhattasaṃyojanañca puggalaṃ deseti bahiddhāsaṃyojanañca.**“Sir, Venerable Sāriputta is in the Eastern Monastery, the stilt longhouse of Migāra’s mother, where he is teaching the mendicants about a person with internal fetters and one with external fetters.*";
P_HTM[442]="*Haṭṭhā, bhante, parisā.**The assembly is overjoyed!*";
P_HTM[443]="*Sādhu, bhante, bhagavā yenāyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**Sir, please go to Venerable Sāriputta out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[444]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[445]="*Atha kho bhagavā—seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evamevaṃ—jetavane antarahito pubbārāme migāramātupāsāde āyasmato sāriputtassa sammukhe pāturahosi.**Then the Buddha, as easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, vanished from Jeta’s Grove and reappeared in the Eastern Monastery, the stilt longhouse of Migāra’s mother, in front of Sāriputta.*";
P_HTM[446]="*Nisīdi bhagavā paññatte āsane.**He sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[447]="*Āyasmāpi kho sāriputto bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**Sāriputta bowed to the Buddha and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[448]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said to him:*";
P_HTM[449]="*“Idha, sāriputta, sambahulā samacittā devatā yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho, sāriputta, tā devatā maṃ etadavocuṃ:**“Just now, Sāriputta, several peaceful-minded deities came up to me, bowed, and stood to one side. Those deities said to me:*";
P_HTM[450]="*‘eso, bhante, āyasmā sāriputto pubbārāme migāramātupāsāde bhikkhūnaṃ ajjhattasaṃyojanañca puggalaṃ deseti bahiddhāsaṃyojanañca.**‘Sir, Venerable Sāriputta is in the Eastern Monastery, the stilt longhouse of Migāra’s mother, where he is teaching the mendicants about a person with internal fetters and one with external fetters.*";
P_HTM[451]="*Haṭṭhā, bhante, parisā.**The assembly is overjoyed!*";
P_HTM[452]="*Sādhu, bhante, bhagavā yena āyasmā sāriputto tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’ti.**Sir, please go to Venerable Sāriputta out of compassion.’*";
P_HTM[453]="*Tā kho pana, sāriputta, devatā dasapi hutvā vīsampi hutvā tiṃsampi hutvā cattālīsampi hutvā paññāsampi hutvā saṭṭhipi hutvā āraggakoṭinitudanamattepi tiṭṭhanti, na ca aññamaññaṃ byābādhenti.**Those deities, though they number ten, twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, or sixty, can stand on the point of a needle without bumping up against each other.*";
P_HTM[454]="*Siyā kho pana, sāriputta, evamassa:**Sāriputta, you might think:*";
P_HTM[455]="*‘tattha nūna tāsaṃ devatānaṃ tathā cittaṃ bhāvitaṃ yena tā devatā dasapi hutvā vīsampi hutvā tiṃsampi hutvā cattālīsampi hutvā paññāsampi hutvā saṭṭhipi hutvā āraggakoṭinitudanamattepi tiṭṭhanti na ca aññamaññaṃ byābādhentī’ti.**‘Surely those deities, since so many of them can stand on the point of a needle without bumping up against each other, must have developed their minds in that place.’*";
P_HTM[456]="*Na kho panetaṃ, sāriputta, evaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.**But you should not see it like this.*";
P_HTM[457]="*Idheva kho, sāriputta, tāsaṃ devatānaṃ tathā cittaṃ bhāvitaṃ, yena tā devatā dasapi hutvā … pe … na ca aññamaññaṃ byābādhenti.**It was right here that those deities developed their minds.*";
P_HTM[458]="*Tasmātiha, sāriputta, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[459]="*‘santindriyā bhavissāma santamānasā’ti.**‘We shall have peaceful faculties and peaceful minds.’*";
P_HTM[460]="*Evañhi vo, sāriputta, sikkhitabbaṃ.**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[461]="*‘Santindriyānañhi vo, sāriputta, santamānasānaṃ santaṃyeva kāyakammaṃ bhavissati santaṃ vacīkammaṃ santaṃ manokammaṃ.**When your faculties and mind are peaceful, your acts of body, speech, and mind will be peaceful, thinking:*";
P_HTM[462]="*Santaṃyeva upahāraṃ upaharissāma sabrahmacārīsū’ti.**‘We shall present the gift of peace to our spiritual companions.’*";
P_HTM[463]="*‘Evañhi vo, sāriputta, sikkhitabbaṃ.**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[464]="*Anassuṃ kho, sāriputta, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā ye imaṃ dhammapariyāyaṃ nāssosun’”ti.**Those wanderers who follow other paths, Sāriputta, who have not heard this exposition of the teaching are lost.”*";
P_HTM[465]="*37**37*";
P_HTM[466]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[467]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā mahākaccāno varaṇāyaṃ viharati bhaddasāritīre.**At one time Venerable Mahākaccāna was staying at Varaṇā, on the bank of the Kaddama Lake.*";
P_HTM[468]="*Atha kho ārāmadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā mahākaccānena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then the brahmin Ārāmadaṇḍa went up to Mahākaccāna, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[469]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho ārāmadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to Mahākaccāna:*";
P_HTM[470]="*“ko nu kho, bho kaccāna, hetu ko paccayo yena khattiyāpi khattiyehi vivadanti, brāhmaṇāpi brāhmaṇehi vivadanti, gahapatikāpi gahapatikehi vivadantī”ti?**“What is the cause, Master Kaccāna, what is the reason why aristocrats fight with aristocrats, brahmins fight with brahmins, and householders fight with householders?”*";
P_HTM[471]="*“Kāmarāgābhinivesavinibandhapaligedhapariyuṭṭhānajjhosānahetu kho, brāhmaṇa, khattiyāpi khattiyehi vivadanti, brāhmaṇāpi brāhmaṇehi vivadanti, gahapatikāpi gahapatikehi vivadantī”ti.**“It is because of their insistence on sensual desire, their shackles, avarice, and attachment, that aristocrats fight with aristocrats, brahmins fight with brahmins, and householders fight with householders.”*";
P_HTM[472]="*“Ko pana, bho kaccāna, hetu ko paccayo yena samaṇāpi samaṇehi vivadantī”ti?**“What is the cause, Master Kaccāna, what is the reason why ascetics fight with ascetics?”*";
P_HTM[473]="*“Diṭṭhirāgābhinivesavinibandhapaligedhapariyuṭṭhānajjhosānahetu kho, brāhmaṇa, samaṇāpi samaṇehi vivadantī”ti.**“It is because of their insistence on views, their shackles, avarice, and attachment, that ascetics fight with ascetics.”*";
P_HTM[474]="*“Atthi pana, bho kaccāna, koci lokasmiṃ yo imañceva kāmarāgābhinivesavinibandhapaligedhapariyuṭṭhānajjhosānaṃ samatikkanto, imañca diṭṭhirāgābhinivesavinibandhapaligedhapariyuṭṭhānajjhosānaṃ samatikkanto”ti?**“Master Kaccāna, is there anyone in the world who has gone beyond the insistence on sensual desire and the insistence on views?”*";
P_HTM[475]="*“Atthi, brāhmaṇa, lokasmiṃ yo imañceva kāmarāgābhinivesavinibandhapaligedhapariyuṭṭhānajjhosānaṃ samatikkanto, imañca diṭṭhirāgābhinivesavinibandhapaligedhapariyuṭṭhānajjhosānaṃ samatikkanto”ti.**“There is, brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[476]="*“Ko pana so, bho kaccāna, lokasmiṃ yo imañceva kāmarāgābhinivesavinibandhapaligedhapariyuṭṭhānajjhosānaṃ samatikkanto, imañca diṭṭhirāgābhinivesavinibandhapaligedhapariyuṭṭhānajjhosānaṃ samatikkanto”ti?**“Who in the world has gone beyond the insistence on sensual desire and the insistence on views?”*";
P_HTM[477]="*“Atthi, brāhmaṇa, puratthimesu janapadesu sāvatthī nāma nagaraṃ.**“In the eastern lands there is a city called Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[478]="*Tattha so bhagavā etarahi viharati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho.**There the Blessed One is now staying, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[479]="*So hi, brāhmaṇa, bhagavā imañceva kāmarāgābhinivesavinibandhapaligedhapariyuṭṭhānajjhosānaṃ samatikkanto, imañca diṭṭhirāgābhinivesavinibandhapaligedhapariyuṭṭhānajjhosānaṃ samatikkanto”ti.**He, brahmin, has gone beyond the insistence on sensual desire and the insistence on views.”*";
P_HTM[480]="*Evaṃ vutte, ārāmadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo uṭṭhāyāsanā ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā dakkhiṇaṃ jāṇumaṇḍalaṃ pathaviyaṃ nihantvā yena bhagavā tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā tikkhattuṃ udānaṃ udānesi:**When this was said, the brahmin Ārāmadaṇḍa got up from his seat, arranged his robe over one shoulder, knelt on his right knee, raised his joined palms toward the Buddha, and was inspired to exclaim three times:*";
P_HTM[481]="*“Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa.**“Homage to that Blessed One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha!*";
P_HTM[482]="*Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa.**Homage to that Blessed One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha!*";
P_HTM[483]="*Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa.**Homage to that Blessed One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha!*";
P_HTM[484]="*Yo hi so bhagavā imañceva kāmarāgābhinivesavinibandhapaligedhapariyuṭṭhānajjhosānaṃ samatikkanto, imañca diṭṭhirāgābhinivesavinibandhapaligedhapariyuṭṭhānajjhosānaṃ samatikkanto”ti.**He who has gone beyond the insistence on sensual desire and the insistence on views.*";
P_HTM[485]="*“Abhikkantaṃ, bho kaccāna, abhikkantaṃ, bho kaccāna.**Excellent, Master Kaccāna! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[486]="*Seyyathāpi, bho kaccāna, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya; andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhotā kaccānena anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, Master Kaccāna has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[487]="*Esāhaṃ, bho kaccāna, taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[488]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ kaccāno dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may Master Kaccāna remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[489]="*38**38*";
P_HTM[490]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā mahākaccāno madhurāyaṃ viharati gundāvane.**At one time Venerable Mahākaccāna was staying near Madhurā, in Gunda’s Grove.*";
P_HTM[491]="*Atha kho kandarāyano brāhmaṇo yenāyasmā mahākaccāno tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā mahākaccānena saddhiṃ … pe … ekamantaṃ nisinno kho kandarāyano brāhmaṇo āyasmantaṃ mahākaccānaṃ etadavoca:**Then the brahmin Kandarāyana went up to Mahākaccāna, and exchanged greetings with him … He sat down to one side and said to Mahākaccāna:*";
P_HTM[492]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bho kaccāna, ‘na samaṇo kaccāno brāhmaṇe jiṇṇe vuddhe mahallake addhagate vayoanuppatte abhivādeti vā paccuṭṭheti vā āsanena vā nimantetī’ti.**“I have heard, Master Kaccāna, that the ascetic Kaccāna doesn’t bow to old brahmins, the elderly and senior, who are advanced in years and have reached the final stage of life; nor does he rise in their presence or offer them a seat.*";
P_HTM[493]="*Tayidaṃ, bho kaccāna, tatheva?**And this is indeed the case,*";
P_HTM[494]="*Na hi bhavaṃ kaccāno brāhmaṇe jiṇṇe vuddhe mahallake addhagate vayoanuppatte abhivādeti vā paccuṭṭheti vā āsanena vā nimanteti.**for the ascetic Kaccāna does not bow to old brahmins, elderly and senior, who are advanced in years and have reached the final stage of life; nor does he rise in their presence or offer them a seat.*";
P_HTM[495]="*Tayidaṃ, bho kaccāna, na sampannamevā”ti.**This is not appropriate, Master Kaccāna.”*";
P_HTM[496]="*“Atthi, brāhmaṇa, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena vuddhabhūmi ca akkhātā daharabhūmi ca.**“There is the stage of an elder and the stage of youth as explained by the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[497]="*Vuddho cepi, brāhmaṇa, hoti āsītiko vā nāvutiko vā vassasatiko vā jātiyā, so ca kāme paribhuñjati kāmamajjhāvasati kāmapariḷāhena pariḍayhati kāmavitakkehi khajjati kāmapariyesanāya ussuko.**If an elder, though eighty, ninety, or a hundred years old, still dwells in the midst of sensual pleasures, enjoying them, consumed by thoughts of them, burning with fever for them, and eagerly seeking more,*";
P_HTM[498]="*Atha kho so bālo na therotveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchati.**they are reckoned as a child, not a senior.*";
P_HTM[499]="*Daharo cepi, brāhmaṇa, hoti yuvā susukāḷakeso bhadrena yobbanena samannāgato paṭhamena vayasā.**If a youth, young, black-haired, blessed with youth, in the prime of life,*";
P_HTM[500]="*So ca na kāme paribhuñjati na kāmamajjhāvasati, na kāmapariḷāhena pariḍayhati, na kāmavitakkehi khajjati, na kāmapariyesanāya ussuko.**does not dwell in the midst of sensual pleasures, enjoying them, consumed by thoughts of them, burning with fever for them, and eagerly seeking more,*";
P_HTM[501]="*Atha kho so paṇḍito therotveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchatī”ti.**they are reckoned as astute, a senior.”*";
P_HTM[502]="*Evaṃ vutte, kandarāyano brāhmaṇo uṭṭhāyāsanā ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā daharānaṃ sataṃ bhikkhūnaṃ pāde sirasā vandati:**When this was said, the brahmin Kandarāyana got up from his seat, placed his robe over one shoulder, and bowed with his head at the feet of the young mendicants, saying,*";
P_HTM[503]="*“vuddhā bhavanto, vuddhabhūmiyaṃ ṭhitā.**“The masters are elders, at the stage of the elder;*";
P_HTM[504]="*Daharā mayaṃ, daharabhūmiyaṃ ṭhitā”ti.**we are youths, at the stage of youth.*";
P_HTM[505]="*“Abhikkantaṃ, bho kaccāna … pe … upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ kaccāno dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**Excellent, Master Kaccāna! … From this day forth, may Master Kaccāna remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[506]="*39**39*";
P_HTM[507]="*“Yasmiṃ, bhikkhave, samaye corā balavanto honti, rājāno tasmiṃ samaye dubbalā honti.**“At a time when bandits are strong, kings are weak.*";
P_HTM[508]="*Tasmiṃ, bhikkhave, samaye rañño na phāsu hoti atiyātuṃ vā niyyātuṃ vā paccantime vā janapade anusaññātuṃ.**Then the king is not at ease when going out or coming back or when touring the provinces.*";
P_HTM[509]="*Brāhmaṇagahapatikānampi tasmiṃ samaye na phāsu hoti atiyātuṃ vā niyyātuṃ vā bāhirāni vā kammantāni paṭivekkhituṃ.**The brahmins and householders, likewise, are not at ease when going out or coming back, or when inspecting their business activities.*";
P_HTM[510]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, yasmiṃ samaye pāpabhikkhū balavanto honti, pesalā bhikkhū tasmiṃ samaye dubbalā honti.**In the same way, at a time when bad mendicants are strong, good-hearted mendicants are weak.*";
P_HTM[511]="*Tasmiṃ, bhikkhave, samaye pesalā bhikkhū tuṇhībhūtā tuṇhībhūtāva saṃghamajjhe saṅkasāyanti paccantime vā janapade acchanti.**Then the good-hearted mendicants continually adhere to silence in the midst of the Saṅgha, or they stay in the borderlands.*";
P_HTM[512]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, hoti bahujanāhitāya bahujanāsukhāya, bahuno janassa anatthāya ahitāya dukkhāya devamanussānaṃ.**This is for the hurt and unhappiness of the people, for the harm, hurt, and suffering of many people, of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[513]="*Yasmiṃ, bhikkhave, samaye rājāno balavanto honti, corā tasmiṃ samaye dubbalā honti.**At a time when kings are strong, bandits are weak.*";
P_HTM[514]="*Tasmiṃ, bhikkhave, samaye rañño phāsu hoti atiyātuṃ vā niyyātuṃ vā paccantime vā janapade anusaññātuṃ.**Then the king is at ease when going out or coming back or when inspecting the provinces.*";
P_HTM[515]="*Brāhmaṇagahapatikānampi tasmiṃ samaye phāsu hoti atiyātuṃ vā niyyātuṃ vā bāhirāni vā kammantāni paṭivekkhituṃ.**The brahmins and householders, likewise, are at ease when going out or coming back, or when inspecting their business activities.*";
P_HTM[516]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, yasmiṃ samaye pesalā bhikkhū balavanto honti, pāpabhikkhū tasmiṃ samaye dubbalā honti.**In the same way, at a time when good-hearted mendicants are strong, bad mendicants are weak.*";
P_HTM[517]="*Tasmiṃ, bhikkhave, samaye pāpabhikkhū tuṇhībhūtā tuṇhībhūtāva saṃghamajjhe saṅkasāyanti, yena vā pana tena pakkamanti.**Then the bad mendicants continually adhere to silence in the midst of the Saṅgha, or they leave for some place or other.*";
P_HTM[518]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, hoti bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya, bahuno janassa atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānan”ti.**This is for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.”*";
P_HTM[519]="*40**40*";
P_HTM[520]="*“Dvinnāhaṃ, bhikkhave, micchāpaṭipattiṃ na vaṇṇemi, gihissa vā pabbajitassa vā.**“Mendicants, I don’t praise wrong practice for these two, for laypeople and renunciates.*";
P_HTM[521]="*Gihī vā, bhikkhave, pabbajito vā micchāpaṭipanno micchāpaṭipattādhikaraṇahetu na ārādhako hoti ñāyaṃ dhammaṃ kusalaṃ.**Because of wrong practice, neither laypeople nor renunciates succeed in completing the procedure of the skillful teaching.*";
P_HTM[522]="*Dvinnāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sammāpaṭipattiṃ vaṇṇemi, gihissa vā pabbajitassa vā.**I praise right practice for these two, for laypeople and renunciates.*";
P_HTM[523]="*Gihī vā, bhikkhave, pabbajito vā sammāpaṭipanno sammāpaṭipattādhikaraṇahetu ārādhako hoti ñāyaṃ dhammaṃ kusalan”ti.**Because of right practice, both laypeople and renunciates succeed in completing the procedure of the skillful teaching.”*";
P_HTM[524]="*41**41*";
P_HTM[525]="*“Ye te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū duggahitehi suttantehi byañjanappatirūpakehi atthañca dhammañca paṭibāhanti te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū bahujanāhitāya paṭipannā bahujanāsukhāya, bahuno janassa anatthāya ahitāya dukkhāya devamanussānaṃ.**“Mendicants, by memorizing the discourses incorrectly, taking only a semblance of the phrasing, some mendicants shut out the meaning and the teaching. They act for the hurt and unhappiness of the people, for the harm, hurt, and suffering of many people, of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[526]="*Bahuñca te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū apuññaṃ pasavanti, te cimaṃ saddhammaṃ antaradhāpenti.**They make much bad karma and make the true teaching disappear.*";
P_HTM[527]="*Ye te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū suggahitehi suttantehi byañjanappatirūpakehi atthañca dhammañca anulomenti te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū bahujanahitāya paṭipannā bahujanasukhāya, bahuno janassa atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**But by memorizing the discourses well, not taking only a semblance of the phrasing, some mendicants reinforce the meaning and the teaching. They act for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of the people, of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[528]="*Bahuñca te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū puññaṃ pasavanti, te cimaṃ saddhammaṃ ṭhapentī”ti.**They make much merit and make the true teaching continue.”*";
P_HTM[529]="*Samacittavaggo catuttho.* **";
P_HTM[530]="*5. Upaññātasuttaṃ**42*";
P_HTM[531]="*“Dvemā, bhikkhave, parisā.**“There are, mendicants, these two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[532]="*Katamā dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[533]="*Uttānā ca parisā gambhīrā ca parisā.**A shallow assembly and a deep assembly.*";
P_HTM[534]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, uttānā parisā?**And what is a shallow assembly?*";
P_HTM[535]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū uddhatā honti unnaḷā capalā mukharā vikiṇṇavācā muṭṭhassatī asampajānā asamāhitā vibbhantacittā pākatindriyā.**An assembly where the mendicants are restless, insolent, fickle, gossipy, loose-tongued, unmindful, lacking situational awareness and immersion, with straying minds and undisciplined faculties.*";
P_HTM[536]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, uttānā parisā.**This is called a shallow assembly.*";
P_HTM[537]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, gambhīrā parisā?**And what is a deep assembly?*";
P_HTM[538]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū anuddhatā honti anunnaḷā acapalā amukharā avikiṇṇavācā upaṭṭhitassatī sampajānā samāhitā ekaggacittā saṃvutindriyā.**An assembly where the mendicants are not restless, insolent, fickle, gossipy, or loose-tongued, but have established mindfulness, situational awareness, immersion, unified minds, and restrained faculties.*";
P_HTM[539]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, gambhīrā parisā.**This is called a deep assembly.*";
P_HTM[540]="*Imā kho, bhikkhave, dve parisā.**These are the two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[541]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imāsaṃ dvinnaṃ parisānaṃ yadidaṃ gambhīrā parisā”ti.**The better of these two assemblies is the deep assembly.”*";
P_HTM[542]="*43**43*";
P_HTM[543]="*“Dvemā, bhikkhave, parisā.**“There are, mendicants, these two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[544]="*Katamā dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[545]="*Vaggā ca parisā samaggā ca parisā.**A divided assembly and a harmonious assembly.*";
P_HTM[546]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, vaggā parisā?**And what is a divided assembly?*";
P_HTM[547]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū bhaṇḍanajātā kalahajātā vivādāpannā aññamaññaṃ mukhasattīhi vitudantā viharanti.**An assembly where the mendicants argue, quarrel, and fight, continually wounding each other with barbed words.*";
P_HTM[548]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, vaggā parisā.**This is called a divided assembly.*";
P_HTM[549]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, samaggā parisā?**And what is a harmonious assembly?*";
P_HTM[550]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū samaggā sammodamānā avivadamānā khīrodakībhūtā aññamaññaṃ piyacakkhūhi sampassantā viharanti.**An assembly where the mendicants live in harmony, appreciating each other, without quarreling, blending like milk and water, and regarding each other with kindly eyes.*";
P_HTM[551]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, samaggā parisā.**This is called a harmonious assembly.*";
P_HTM[552]="*Imā kho, bhikkhave, dve parisā.**These are the two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[553]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imāsaṃ dvinnaṃ parisānaṃ yadidaṃ samaggā parisā”ti.**The better of these two assemblies is the harmonious assembly.”*";
P_HTM[554]="*44**44*";
P_HTM[555]="*“Dvemā, bhikkhave, parisā.**“There are, mendicants, these two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[556]="*Katamā dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[557]="*Anaggavatī ca parisā aggavatī ca parisā.**An assembly of the worst and an assembly of the best.*";
P_HTM[558]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, anaggavatī parisā?**And what is an assembly of the worst?*";
P_HTM[559]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ therā bhikkhū bāhulikā honti sāthalikā, okkamane pubbaṅgamā, paviveke nikkhittadhurā, na vīriyaṃ ārabhanti appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāya.**An assembly where the senior mendicants are indulgent and slack, leaders in backsliding, neglecting seclusion, not rousing energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.*";
P_HTM[560]="*Tesaṃ pacchimā janatā diṭṭhānugatiṃ āpajjati.**Those who come after follow their example.*";
P_HTM[561]="*Sāpi hoti bāhulikā sāthalikā, okkamane pubbaṅgamā, paviveke nikkhittadhurā, na vīriyaṃ ārabhati appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāya.**They too become indulgent and slack, leaders in backsliding, neglecting seclusion, not rousing energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.*";
P_HTM[562]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, anaggavatī parisā.**This is called an assembly of the worst.*";
P_HTM[563]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, aggavatī parisā?**And what is an assembly of the best?*";
P_HTM[564]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ therā bhikkhū na bāhulikā honti na sāthalikā, okkamane nikkhittadhurā, paviveke pubbaṅgamā, vīriyaṃ ārabhanti appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāya.**An assembly where the senior mendicants are not indulgent or slack, nor are they backsliders; instead, they take the lead in seclusion, rousing energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.*";
P_HTM[565]="*Tesaṃ pacchimā janatā diṭṭhānugatiṃ āpajjati.**Those who come after follow their example.*";
P_HTM[566]="*Sāpi hoti na bāhulikā na sāthalikā, okkamane nikkhittadhurā, paviveke pubbaṅgamā, vīriyaṃ ārabhati appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāya.**They too are not indulgent or slack, nor are they backsliders; instead, they take the lead in seclusion, rousing energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.*";
P_HTM[567]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, aggavatī parisā.**This is called an assembly of the best.*";
P_HTM[568]="*Imā kho, bhikkhave, dve parisā.**These are the two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[569]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imāsaṃ dvinnaṃ parisānaṃ yadidaṃ aggavatī parisā”ti.**The better of these two assemblies is the assembly of the best.”*";
P_HTM[570]="*45**45*";
P_HTM[571]="*“Dvemā, bhikkhave, parisā.**“There are, mendicants, these two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[572]="*Katamā dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[573]="*Anariyā ca parisā ariyā ca parisā.**An ignoble assembly and a noble assembly.*";
P_HTM[574]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, anariyā parisā?**And what is an ignoble assembly?*";
P_HTM[575]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānanti.**An assembly where the mendicants don’t truly understand: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[576]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, anariyā parisā.**This is called an ignoble assembly.*";
P_HTM[577]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, ariyā parisā?**And what is a noble assembly?*";
P_HTM[578]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānanti.**An assembly where the mendicants truly understand: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[579]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ariyā parisā.**This is called a noble assembly.*";
P_HTM[580]="*Imā kho, bhikkhave, dve parisā.**These are the two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[581]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imāsaṃ dvinnaṃ parisānaṃ yadidaṃ ariyā parisā”ti.**The better of these two assemblies is the noble assembly.”*";
P_HTM[582]="*46**46*";
P_HTM[583]="*“Dvemā, bhikkhave, parisā.**“There are, mendicants, these two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[584]="*Katamā dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[585]="*Parisākasaṭo ca parisāmaṇḍo ca.**An assembly of the dregs and an assembly of the cream.*";
P_HTM[586]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, parisākasaṭo?**And what is an assembly of the dregs?*";
P_HTM[587]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū chandāgatiṃ gacchanti, dosāgatiṃ gacchanti, mohāgatiṃ gacchanti, bhayāgatiṃ gacchanti.**An assembly where the mendicants make decisions prejudiced by favoritism, hostility, stupidity, and cowardice.*";
P_HTM[588]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, parisākasaṭo.**This is called an assembly of the dregs.*";
P_HTM[589]="*Katamo ca, bhikkhave, parisāmaṇḍo?**And what is an assembly of the cream?*";
P_HTM[590]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū na chandāgatiṃ gacchanti, na dosāgatiṃ gacchanti, na mohāgatiṃ gacchanti, na bhayāgatiṃ gacchanti.**An assembly where the mendicants make decisions unprejudiced by favoritism, hostility, stupidity, and cowardice.*";
P_HTM[591]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, parisāmaṇḍo.**This is called an assembly of the cream.*";
P_HTM[592]="*Imā kho, bhikkhave, dve parisā.**These are the two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[593]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imāsaṃ dvinnaṃ parisānaṃ yadidaṃ parisāmaṇḍo”ti.**The better of these two assemblies is the assembly of the cream.”*";
P_HTM[594]="*47**47*";
P_HTM[595]="*“Dvemā, bhikkhave, parisā.**“There are, mendicants, these two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[596]="*Katamā dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[597]="*Okkācitavinītā parisā nopaṭipucchāvinītā, paṭipucchāvinītā parisā nookkācitavinītā.**An assembly educated in fancy talk, not in questioning, and an assembly educated in questioning, not in fancy talk.*";
P_HTM[598]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, okkācitavinītā parisā nopaṭipucchāvinītā?**And what is an assembly educated in fancy talk, not in questioning?*";
P_HTM[599]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū ye te suttantā tathāgatabhāsitā gambhīrā gambhīratthā lokuttarā suññatāpaṭisaṃyuttā tesu bhaññamānesu na sussūsanti na sotaṃ odahanti na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti na ca te dhamme uggahetabbaṃ pariyāpuṇitabbaṃ maññanti.**It is an assembly where, when discourses spoken by the Realized One—deep, profound, transcendent, dealing with emptiness—are being recited the mendicants do not want to listen. They don’t pay attention or apply their minds to understand them, nor do they think those teachings are worth learning and memorizing.*";
P_HTM[600]="*Ye pana te suttantā kavitā kāveyyā cittakkharā cittabyañjanā bāhirakā sāvakabhāsitā tesu bhaññamānesu sussūsanti sotaṃ odahanti aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, te dhamme uggahetabbaṃ pariyāpuṇitabbaṃ maññanti, te ca taṃ dhammaṃ pariyāpuṇitvā na ceva aññamaññaṃ paṭipucchanti na ca paṭivicaranti:**But when discourses composed by poets—poetry, with fancy words and phrases, composed by outsiders or spoken by disciples—are being recited the mendicants do want to listen. They pay attention and apply their minds to understand them, and they think those teachings are worth learning and memorizing. But when they’ve learned those teachings they don’t question or examine each other, saying:*";
P_HTM[601]="*‘idaṃ kathaṃ, imassa ko attho’ti?**‘Why does it say this? What does that mean?’*";
P_HTM[602]="*Te avivaṭañceva na vivaranti, anuttānīkatañca na uttānīkaronti, anekavihitesu ca kaṅkhāṭhāniyesu dhammesu kaṅkhaṃ na paṭivinodenti.**So they don’t clarify what is unclear, or reveal what is obscure, or dispel doubt regarding the many doubtful matters.*";
P_HTM[603]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, okkācitavinītā parisā no paṭipucchāvinītā.**This is called an assembly educated in fancy talk, not in questioning.*";
P_HTM[604]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, paṭipucchāvinītā parisā nookkācitavinītā?**And what is an assembly educated in questioning, not in fancy talk?*";
P_HTM[605]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū ye te suttantā kavitā kāveyyā cittakkharā cittabyañjanā bāhirakā sāvakabhāsitā tesu bhaññamānesu na sussūsanti na sotaṃ odahanti na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, na ca te dhamme uggahetabbaṃ pariyāpuṇitabbaṃ maññanti.**It is an assembly where, when discourses composed by poets—poetry, with fancy words and phrases, composed by outsiders or spoken by disciples—are being recited the mendicants do not want to listen. They don’t pay attention or apply their minds to understand them, nor do they think those teachings are worth learning and memorizing.*";
P_HTM[606]="*Ye pana te suttantā tathāgatabhāsitā gambhīrā gambhīratthā lokuttarā suññatāpaṭisaṃyuttā tesu bhaññamānesu sussūsanti sotaṃ odahanti aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, te ca dhamme uggahetabbaṃ pariyāpuṇitabbaṃ maññanti.**But when discourses spoken by the Realized One—deep, profound, transcendent, dealing with emptiness—are being recited the mendicants do want to listen. They pay attention and apply their minds to understand them, and they think those teachings are worth learning and memorizing.*";
P_HTM[607]="*Te taṃ dhammaṃ pariyāpuṇitvā aññamaññaṃ paṭipucchanti paṭivicaranti:**And when they’ve learned those teachings they question and examine each other, saying:*";
P_HTM[608]="*‘idaṃ kathaṃ, imassa ko attho’ti?**‘Why does it say this? What does that mean?’*";
P_HTM[609]="*Te avivaṭañceva vivaranti, anuttānīkatañca uttānīkaronti, anekavihitesu ca kaṅkhāṭhāniyesu dhammesu kaṅkhaṃ paṭivinodenti.**So they clarify what is unclear, reveal what is obscure, and dispel doubt regarding the many doubtful matters.*";
P_HTM[610]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, paṭipucchāvinītā parisā nookkācitavinītā.**This is called an assembly educated in questioning, not in fancy talk.*";
P_HTM[611]="*Imā kho, bhikkhave, dve parisā.**These are the two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[612]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imāsaṃ dvinnaṃ parisānaṃ yadidaṃ paṭipucchāvinītā parisā nookkācitavinītā”ti.**The better of these two assemblies is the assembly educated in questioning, not in fancy talk.”*";
P_HTM[613]="*48**48*";
P_HTM[614]="*“Dvemā, bhikkhave, parisā.**“There are, mendicants, these two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[615]="*Katamā dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[616]="*Āmisagaru parisā no saddhammagaru, saddhammagaru parisā no āmisagaru.**An assembly that values material things, not the true teaching, and an assembly that values the true teaching, not material things.*";
P_HTM[617]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, āmisagaru parisā no saddhammagaru?**And what is an assembly that values material things, not the true teaching?*";
P_HTM[618]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū gihīnaṃ odātavasanānaṃ sammukhā aññamaññassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsanti:**It is an assembly where the mendicants praise each other in front of the white-clothed laypeople, saying:*";
P_HTM[619]="*‘asuko bhikkhu ubhatobhāgavimutto, asuko paññāvimutto, asuko kāyasakkhī, asuko diṭṭhippatto, asuko saddhāvimutto, asuko dhammānusārī, asuko saddhānusārī, asuko sīlavā kalyāṇadhammo, asuko dussīlo pāpadhammo’ti.**‘The mendicant so-and-so is freed both ways; so-and-so is freed by wisdom; so-and-so is a personal witness; so-and-so is attained to view; so-and-so is freed by faith; so-and-so is a follower of the teachings; so-and-so is a follower by faith; so-and-so is ethical, of good character; so-and-so is unethical, of bad character.’*";
P_HTM[620]="*Te tena lābhaṃ labhanti.**In this way they get material things.*";
P_HTM[621]="*Te taṃ lābhaṃ labhitvā gathitā mucchitā ajjhopannā anādīnavadassāvino anissaraṇapaññā paribhuñjanti.**And when they get these things, they use them tied, infatuated, attached, blind to the drawbacks, and not understanding the escape.*";
P_HTM[622]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, āmisagaru parisā no saddhammagaru.**This is called an assembly that values material things, not the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[623]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, saddhammagaru parisā noāmisagaru?**And what is an assembly that values the true teaching, not material things?*";
P_HTM[624]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū gihīnaṃ odātavasanānaṃ sammukhā aññamaññassa vaṇṇaṃ na bhāsanti:**It is an assembly where the mendicants don’t praise each other in front of the white-clothed laypeople, saying:*";
P_HTM[625]="*‘asuko bhikkhu ubhatobhāgavimutto, asuko paññāvimutto, asuko kāyasakkhī, asuko diṭṭhippatto, asuko saddhāvimutto, asuko dhammānusārī, asuko saddhānusārī, asuko sīlavā kalyāṇadhammo, asuko dussīlo pāpadhammo’ti.**‘The mendicant so-and-so is freed both ways; so-and-so is freed by wisdom; so-and-so is a personal witness; so-and-so is attained to view; so-and-so is freed by faith; so-and-so is a follower of the teachings; so-and-so is a follower by faith; so-and-so is ethical, of good character; so-and-so is unethical, of bad character.’*";
P_HTM[626]="*Te tena lābhaṃ labhanti.**In this way they get material things.*";
P_HTM[627]="*Te taṃ lābhaṃ labhitvā agathitā amucchitā anajjhosannā ādīnavadassāvino nissaraṇapaññā paribhuñjanti.**And when they get these things, they use them untied, uninfatuated, unattached, seeing the drawbacks, and understanding the escape.*";
P_HTM[628]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, saddhammagaru parisā noāmisagaru.**This is called an assembly that values the true teaching, not material things.*";
P_HTM[629]="*Imā kho, bhikkhave, dve parisā.**These are the two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[630]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imāsaṃ dvinnaṃ parisānaṃ yadidaṃ saddhammagaru parisā noāmisagarū”ti.**The better of these two assemblies is the assembly that values the true teaching, not material things.”*";
P_HTM[631]="*49**49*";
P_HTM[632]="*“Dvemā, bhikkhave, parisā.**“There are, mendicants, these two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[633]="*Katamā dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[634]="*Visamā ca parisā samā ca parisā.**An unjust assembly and a just assembly.*";
P_HTM[635]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, visamā parisā?**And what is an unjust assembly?*";
P_HTM[636]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ adhammakammāni pavattanti dhammakammāni nappavattanti, avinayakammāni pavattanti vinayakammāni nappavattanti, adhammakammāni dippanti dhammakammāni na dippanti, avinayakammāni dippanti vinayakammāni na dippanti.**An assembly where legal acts against the teaching proceed, while legal acts in line with the teaching don’t proceed. Legal acts against the training proceed, while legal acts in line with the training don’t proceed. Legal acts against the teaching are explained, while legal acts in line with the teaching aren’t explained. Legal acts against the training are explained, while legal acts in line with the training aren’t explained.*";
P_HTM[637]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, visamā parisā. ()**This is called an unjust assembly.*";
P_HTM[638]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, samā parisā?**And what is a just assembly?*";
P_HTM[639]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ dhammakammāni pavattanti adhammakammāni nappavattanti, vinayakammāni pavattanti avinayakammāni nappavattanti, dhammakammāni dippanti adhammakammāni na dippanti, vinayakammāni dippanti avinayakammāni na dippanti.**An assembly where legal acts in line with the teaching proceed, while legal acts against the teaching don’t proceed. Legal acts in line with the training proceed, while legal acts against the training don’t proceed. Legal acts in line with the teaching are explained, while legal acts against the teaching aren’t explained. Legal acts in line with the training are explained, while legal acts against the training aren’t explained.*";
P_HTM[640]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, samā parisā. ()**This is called a just assembly.*";
P_HTM[641]="*Imā kho, bhikkhave, dve parisā.**These are the two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[642]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imāsaṃ dvinnaṃ parisānaṃ yadidaṃ samā parisā”ti.**The better of these two assemblies is the just assembly.”*";
P_HTM[643]="*50**50*";
P_HTM[644]="*“Dvemā, bhikkhave, parisā.**“There are, mendicants, these two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[645]="*Katamā dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[646]="*Adhammikā ca parisā dhammikā ca parisā … pe … imā kho, bhikkhave, dve parisā.**An unprincipled assembly and a principled assembly …*";
P_HTM[647]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imāsaṃ dvinnaṃ parisānaṃ yadidaṃ dhammikā parisā”ti.**The better of these two assemblies is the principled assembly.”*";
P_HTM[648]="*51**51*";
P_HTM[649]="*“Dvemā, bhikkhave, parisā.**“There are, mendicants, these two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[650]="*Katamā dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[651]="*Adhammavādinī ca parisā dhammavādinī ca parisā.**An assembly with unprincipled speech, and an assembly with principled speech.*";
P_HTM[652]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, adhammavādinī parisā?**And what is an assembly with unprincipled speech?*";
P_HTM[653]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū adhikaraṇaṃ ādiyanti dhammikaṃ vā adhammikaṃ vā.**It is an assembly where the mendicants take up disciplinary issues, whether legitimate or not.*";
P_HTM[654]="*Te taṃ adhikaraṇaṃ ādiyitvā na ceva aññamaññaṃ saññāpenti na ca saññattiṃ upagacchanti, na ca nijjhāpenti na ca nijjhattiṃ upagacchanti.**But they don’t persuade each other or allow themselves to be persuaded, nor do they convince each other or allow themselves to be convinced.*";
P_HTM[655]="*Te asaññattibalā anijjhattibalā appaṭinissaggamantino tameva adhikaraṇaṃ thāmasā parāmāsā abhinivissa voharanti:**Unable to persuade or convince each other, they can’t let go of their opinions. They obstinately stick to that disciplinary issue, insisting that:*";
P_HTM[656]="*‘idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.**‘This is the only truth, other ideas are silly.’*";
P_HTM[657]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, adhammavādinī parisā.**This is called an assembly with unprincipled speech.*";
P_HTM[658]="*Katamā ca, bhikkhave, dhammavādinī parisā?**And what is an assembly with principled speech?*";
P_HTM[659]="*Idha, bhikkhave, yassaṃ parisāyaṃ bhikkhū adhikaraṇaṃ ādiyanti dhammikaṃ vā adhammikaṃ vā.**It is an assembly where the mendicants take up disciplinary issues, whether legitimate or not.*";
P_HTM[660]="*Te taṃ adhikaraṇaṃ ādiyitvā aññamaññaṃ saññāpenti ceva saññattiñca upagacchanti, nijjhāpenti ceva nijjhattiñca upagacchanti.**Then they persuade each other or allow themselves to be persuaded, and they convince each other or allow themselves to be convinced.*";
P_HTM[661]="*Te saññattibalā nijjhattibalā paṭinissaggamantino, na tameva adhikaraṇaṃ thāmasā parāmāsā abhinivissa voharanti:**Since they are able to persuade and convince each other, they let go of their opinions. They don’t obstinately stick to that disciplinary issue or insist that:*";
P_HTM[662]="*‘idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.**‘This is the only truth, other ideas are silly.’*";
P_HTM[663]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, dhammavādinī parisā.**This is called an assembly with principled speech.*";
P_HTM[664]="*Imā kho, bhikkhave, dve parisā.**These are the two assemblies.*";
P_HTM[665]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imāsaṃ dvinnaṃ parisānaṃ yadidaṃ dhammavādinī parisā”ti.**The better of these two assemblies is the assembly with principled speech.”*";
P_HTM[666]="*Parisavaggo pañcamo.* **";
P_HTM[667]="*Uttānā vaggā aggavatī,* **";
P_HTM[668]="*Ariyā kasaṭo ca pañcamo;* **";
P_HTM[669]="*Okkācitaāmisañceva,* **";
P_HTM[670]="*Visamā adhammādhammiyena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[671]="*Paṭhamo paṇṇāsako samatto.* **";
P_HTM[672]="*6. Saṃyojanasuttaṃ**52*";
P_HTM[673]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, puggalā loke uppajjamānā uppajjanti bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya, bahuno janassa atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**“Two people, mendicants, arise in the world for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[674]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[675]="*Tathāgato ca arahaṃ sammāsambuddho, rājā ca cakkavattī.**The Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha; and the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[676]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve puggalā loke uppajjamānā uppajjanti bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya, bahuno janassa atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānan”ti.**These two people arise in the world for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.”*";
P_HTM[677]="*53**53*";
P_HTM[678]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, puggalā loke uppajjamānā uppajjanti acchariyamanussā.**“Two people, mendicants, arise in the world who are incredible human beings.*";
P_HTM[679]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[680]="*Tathāgato ca arahaṃ sammāsambuddho, rājā ca cakkavattī.**The Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha; and the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[681]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve puggalā loke uppajjamānā uppajjanti acchariyamanussā”ti.**These are the two people who arise in the world who are incredible human beings.”*";
P_HTM[682]="*54**54*";
P_HTM[683]="*“Dvinnaṃ, bhikkhave, puggalānaṃ kālakiriyā bahuno janassa anutappā hoti.**“There are two people, mendicants, whose death is regretted by many people.*";
P_HTM[684]="*Katamesaṃ dvinnaṃ?**What two?*";
P_HTM[685]="*Tathāgatassa ca arahato sammāsambuddhassa, rañño ca cakkavattissa.**The Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha; and the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[686]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, dvinnaṃ puggalānaṃ kālakiriyā bahuno janassa anutappā hotī”ti.**These are the two people, mendicants, whose death is regretted by many people.”*";
P_HTM[687]="*55**55*";
P_HTM[688]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, thūpārahā.**“Mendicants, these two are worthy of a monument.*";
P_HTM[689]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[690]="*Tathāgato ca arahaṃ sammāsambuddho, rājā ca cakkavattī.**The Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha; and the wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[691]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve thūpārahā”ti.**These are the two who are worthy of a monument.”*";
P_HTM[692]="*56**56*";
P_HTM[693]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, buddhā.**“Mendicants, there are two kinds of Buddhas.*";
P_HTM[694]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[695]="*Tathāgato ca arahaṃ sammāsambuddho, paccekabuddho ca.**The Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha; and the Buddha awakened for themselves.*";
P_HTM[696]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve buddhā”ti.**These are the two kinds of Buddhas.”*";
P_HTM[697]="*57**57*";
P_HTM[698]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, asaniyā phalantiyā na santasanti.**“These two, mendicants, are not startled by a crack of thunder.*";
P_HTM[699]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[700]="*Bhikkhu ca khīṇāsavo, hatthājānīyo ca.**A mendicant who has ended defilements; and a thoroughbred elephant.*";
P_HTM[701]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve asaniyā phalantiyā na santasantī”ti.**These are the two who are not startled by a crack of thunder.”*";
P_HTM[702]="*58**58*";
P_HTM[703]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, asaniyā phalantiyā na santasanti.**“These two, mendicants, are not startled by a crack of thunder.*";
P_HTM[704]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[705]="*Bhikkhu ca khīṇāsavo, assājānīyo ca.**A mendicant who has ended defilements; and a thoroughbred horse.*";
P_HTM[706]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve asaniyā phalantiyā na santasantī”ti.**These are the two who are not startled by a crack of thunder.”*";
P_HTM[707]="*59**59*";
P_HTM[708]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, asaniyā phalantiyā na santasanti.**“These two, mendicants, are not startled by a crack of thunder.*";
P_HTM[709]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[710]="*Bhikkhu ca khīṇāsavo, sīho ca migarājā.**A mendicant who has ended defilements; and a lion, king of beasts.*";
P_HTM[711]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve asaniyā phalantiyā na santasantī”ti.**These are the two who are not startled by a crack of thunder.”*";
P_HTM[712]="*60**60*";
P_HTM[713]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, atthavase sampassamānā kiṃpurisā mānusiṃ vācaṃ na bhāsanti.**“Fauns see two reasons not to use human speech.*";
P_HTM[714]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[715]="*Mā ca musā bhaṇimhā, mā ca paraṃ abhūtena abbhācikkhimhāti.**Thinking: ‘May we not lie, and may we not misrepresent others with falsehoods.’*";
P_HTM[716]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve atthavase sampassamānā kiṃpurisā mānusiṃ vācaṃ na bhāsantī”ti.**Fauns see two reasons not to use human speech.”*";
P_HTM[717]="*61**61*";
P_HTM[718]="*“Dvinnaṃ dhammānaṃ, bhikkhave, atitto appaṭivāno mātugāmo kālaṃ karoti.**“Mendicants, females die without getting enough of two things.*";
P_HTM[719]="*Katamesaṃ dvinnaṃ?**What two?*";
P_HTM[720]="*Methunasamāpattiyā ca vijāyanassa ca.**Sexual intercourse and giving birth.*";
P_HTM[721]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, dvinnaṃ dhammānaṃ atitto appaṭivāno mātugāmo kālaṃ karotī”ti.**Females die without getting enough of these two things.”*";
P_HTM[722]="*62**62*";
P_HTM[723]="*“Asantasannivāsañca vo, bhikkhave, desessāmi santasannivāsañca.**“Mendicants, I will teach you about living with bad people and living with good people.*";
P_HTM[724]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[725]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[726]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[727]="*“Kathañca, bhikkhave, asantasannivāso hoti, kathañca asanto sannivasanti?**“What is it like living with bad people? How do bad people live together?*";
P_HTM[728]="*Idha, bhikkhave, therassa bhikkhuno evaṃ hoti:**It’s when a senior mendicant thinks:*";
P_HTM[729]="*‘theropi maṃ na vadeyya, majjhimopi maṃ na vadeyya, navopi maṃ na vadeyya;**‘No mendicant, whether senior, middle, or junior, should admonish me;*";
P_HTM[730]="*therampāhaṃ na vadeyyaṃ, majjhimampāhaṃ na vadeyyaṃ, navampāhaṃ na vadeyyaṃ.**and I shouldn’t admonish any mendicant, whether senior, middle, or junior.*";
P_HTM[731]="*Thero cepi maṃ vadeyya ahitānukampī maṃ vadeyya no hitānukampī, noti naṃ vadeyyaṃ viheṭheyyaṃ passampissa nappaṭikareyyaṃ.**If a mendicant—whether senior, middle, or junior—were to admonish me, they wouldn’t be sympathetic, and I’d bother them by saying “No!” And anyway I wouldn’t deal with it even if I saw what I did wrong.’*";
P_HTM[732]="*Majjhimo cepi maṃ vadeyya … pe … navo cepi maṃ vadeyya, ahitānukampī maṃ vadeyya no hitānukampī, noti naṃ vadeyyaṃ viheṭheyyaṃ passampissa nappaṭikareyyaṃ’.* **";
P_HTM[733]="*Majjhimassapi bhikkhuno evaṃ hoti … pe … navassapi bhikkhuno evaṃ hoti:**And a middle or a junior mendicant also thinks:*";
P_HTM[734]="*‘theropi maṃ na vadeyya, majjhimopi maṃ na vadeyya, navopi maṃ na vadeyya;**‘No mendicant, whether senior, middle, or junior, should admonish me;*";
P_HTM[735]="*therampāhaṃ na vadeyyaṃ, majjhimampāhaṃ na vadeyyaṃ, navampāhaṃ na vadeyyaṃ.**and I shouldn’t admonish any mendicant, whether senior, middle, or junior.*";
P_HTM[736]="*Thero cepi maṃ vadeyya ahitānukampī maṃ vadeyya no hitānukampī noti naṃ vadeyyaṃ viheṭheyyaṃ passampissa nappaṭikareyyaṃ.**If a mendicant—whether senior, middle, or junior—were to admonish me, they wouldn’t be sympathetic, and I’d bother them by saying “No!” And anyway I wouldn’t deal with it even if I saw what I did wrong.’*";
P_HTM[737]="*Majjhimo cepi maṃ vadeyya … navo cepi maṃ vadeyya ahitānukampī maṃ vadeyya no hitānukampī, noti naṃ vadeyyaṃ viheṭheyyaṃ passampissa nappaṭikareyyaṃ’.* **";
P_HTM[738]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, asantasannivāso hoti, evañca asanto sannivasanti.**That’s what it’s like living with bad people; that’s how bad people live together.*";
P_HTM[739]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, santasannivāso hoti, kathañca santo sannivasanti?**What is it like living with good people? How do good people live together?*";
P_HTM[740]="*Idha, bhikkhave, therassa bhikkhuno evaṃ hoti:**It’s when a senior mendicant thinks:*";
P_HTM[741]="*‘theropi maṃ vadeyya, majjhimopi maṃ vadeyya, navopi maṃ vadeyya;**‘Any mendicant, whether senior, middle, or junior, should admonish me;*";
P_HTM[742]="*therampāhaṃ vadeyyaṃ, majjhimampāhaṃ vadeyyaṃ, navampāhaṃ vadeyyaṃ.**and I should admonish any mendicant, whether senior, middle, or junior.*";
P_HTM[743]="*Thero cepi maṃ vadeyya hitānukampī maṃ vadeyya no ahitānukampī, sādhūti naṃ vadeyyaṃ na naṃ viheṭheyyaṃ passampissa paṭikareyyaṃ.**If a mendicant—whether senior, middle, or junior—were to admonish me, they’d be sympathetic, so I wouldn’t bother them, but say “Thank you!” And I’d deal with it when I saw what I did wrong.’*";
P_HTM[744]="*Majjhimo cepi maṃ vadeyya … pe … navo cepi maṃ vadeyya hitānukampī maṃ vadeyya no ahitānukampī, sādhūti naṃ vadeyyaṃ na naṃ viheṭheyyaṃ passampissa paṭikareyyaṃ’.* **";
P_HTM[745]="*Majjhimassapi bhikkhuno evaṃ hoti … pe … navassapi bhikkhuno evaṃ hoti:**And a middle or a junior mendicant also thinks:*";
P_HTM[746]="*‘theropi maṃ vadeyya, majjhimopi maṃ vadeyya, navopi maṃ vadeyya;**‘Any mendicant, whether senior, middle, or junior, may admonish me;*";
P_HTM[747]="*therampāhaṃ vadeyyaṃ, majjhimampāhaṃ vadeyyaṃ, navampāhaṃ vadeyyaṃ.**and I’ll admonish any mendicant, whether senior, middle, or junior.*";
P_HTM[748]="*Thero cepi maṃ vadeyya hitānukampī maṃ vadeyya no ahitānukampī, sādhūti naṃ vadeyyaṃ na naṃ viheṭheyyaṃ passampissa paṭikareyyaṃ.**If a mendicant—whether senior, middle, or junior—were to admonish me, they’d be sympathetic, so I wouldn’t bother them, but say “Thank you!” And I’d deal with it when I saw what I did wrong.’*";
P_HTM[749]="*Majjhimo cepi maṃ vadeyya … pe … navo cepi maṃ vadeyya hitānukampī maṃ vadeyya no ahitānukampī, sādhūti naṃ vadeyyaṃ na naṃ viheṭheyyaṃ passampissa paṭikareyyaṃ’.* **";
P_HTM[750]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, santasannivāso hoti, evañca santo sannivasantī”ti.**That’s what it’s like living with good people; that’s how good people live together.”*";
P_HTM[751]="*63**63*";
P_HTM[752]="*“Yasmiṃ, bhikkhave, adhikaraṇe ubhato vacīsaṃsāro diṭṭhipaḷāso cetaso āghāto appaccayo anabhiraddhi ajjhattaṃ avūpasantaṃ hoti, tasmetaṃ, bhikkhave, adhikaraṇe pāṭikaṅkhaṃ:**“In a disciplinary issue, when the tale-bearing on both sides—with contempt for each other’s views, resentful, bitter, and exasperated—is not settled internally, you can expect that this disciplinary issue will be*";
P_HTM[753]="*‘dīghattāya kharattāya vāḷattāya saṃvattissati, bhikkhū ca na phāsuṃ viharissanti’.**long, fractious, and troublesome, and the mendicants won’t live comfortably.*";
P_HTM[754]="*Yasmiñca kho, bhikkhave, adhikaraṇe ubhato vacīsaṃsāro diṭṭhipaḷāso cetaso āghāto appaccayo anabhiraddhi ajjhattaṃ suvūpasantaṃ hoti, tasmetaṃ, bhikkhave, adhikaraṇe pāṭikaṅkhaṃ:**In a disciplinary issue, when the tale-bearing on both sides—with contempt for each other’s views, resentful, bitter, and exasperated—is well settled internally, you can expect that this disciplinary issue*";
P_HTM[755]="*‘na dīghattāya kharattāya vāḷattāya saṃvattissati, bhikkhū ca phāsuṃ viharissantī’”ti.**won’t lead to lasting acrimony and enmity, and the mendicants will live comfortably.”*";
P_HTM[756]="*Puggalavaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[757]="*7. Kaṇhasuttaṃ**64*";
P_HTM[758]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, sukhāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[759]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[760]="*Gihisukhañca pabbajitasukhañca.**The happiness of laypeople, and the happiness of renunciates.*";
P_HTM[761]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve sukhāni.**These are the two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[762]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ sukhānaṃ yadidaṃ pabbajitasukhan”ti.**The better of these two kinds of happiness is the happiness of renunciates.”*";
P_HTM[763]="*65**65*";
P_HTM[764]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, sukhāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[765]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[766]="*Kāmasukhañca nekkhammasukhañca.**Sensual happiness and the happiness of renunciation.*";
P_HTM[767]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve sukhāni.**These are the two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[768]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ sukhānaṃ yadidaṃ nekkhammasukhan”ti.**The better of these two kinds of happiness is the happiness of renunciation.”*";
P_HTM[769]="*66**66*";
P_HTM[770]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, sukhāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[771]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[772]="*Upadhisukhañca nirupadhisukhañca.**The happiness of attachments, and the happiness of no attachments.*";
P_HTM[773]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve sukhāni.**These are the two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[774]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ sukhānaṃ yadidaṃ nirupadhisukhan”ti.**The better of these two kinds of happiness is the happiness of no attachments.”*";
P_HTM[775]="*67**67*";
P_HTM[776]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, sukhāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[777]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[778]="*Sāsavasukhañca anāsavasukhañca.**Defiled happiness and undefiled happiness.*";
P_HTM[779]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve sukhāni.**These are the two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[780]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ sukhānaṃ yadidaṃ anāsavasukhan”ti.**The better of these two kinds of happiness is the happiness of no defilements.”*";
P_HTM[781]="*68**68*";
P_HTM[782]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, sukhāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[783]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[784]="*Sāmisañca sukhaṃ nirāmisañca sukhaṃ.**Material happiness and spiritual happiness.*";
P_HTM[785]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve sukhāni.**These are the two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[786]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ sukhānaṃ yadidaṃ nirāmisaṃ sukhan”ti.**The better of these two kinds of happiness is spiritual happiness.”*";
P_HTM[787]="*69**69*";
P_HTM[788]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, sukhāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[789]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[790]="*Ariyasukhañca anariyasukhañca.**Noble happiness and ignoble happiness.*";
P_HTM[791]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve sukhāni.**These are the two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[792]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ sukhānaṃ yadidaṃ ariyasukhan”ti.**The better of these two kinds of happiness is noble happiness.”*";
P_HTM[793]="*70**70*";
P_HTM[794]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, sukhāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[795]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[796]="*Kāyikañca sukhaṃ cetasikañca sukhaṃ.**Physical happiness and mental happiness.*";
P_HTM[797]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve sukhāni.**These are the two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[798]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ sukhānaṃ yadidaṃ cetasikaṃ sukhan”ti.**The better of these two kinds of happiness is mental happiness.”*";
P_HTM[799]="*71**71*";
P_HTM[800]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, sukhāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[801]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[802]="*Sappītikañca sukhaṃ nippītikañca sukhaṃ.**Happiness with rapture and happiness free of rapture.*";
P_HTM[803]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve sukhāni.**These are the two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[804]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ sukhānaṃ yadidaṃ nippītikaṃ sukhan”ti.**The better of these two kinds of happiness is happiness free of rapture.”*";
P_HTM[805]="*72**72*";
P_HTM[806]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, sukhāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[807]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[808]="*Sātasukhañca upekkhāsukhañca.**The happiness of pleasure and the happiness of equanimity.*";
P_HTM[809]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve sukhāni.**These are the two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[810]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ sukhānaṃ yadidaṃ upekkhāsukhan”ti.**The better of these two kinds of happiness is the happiness of equanimity.”*";
P_HTM[811]="*73**73*";
P_HTM[812]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, sukhāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[813]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[814]="*Samādhisukhañca asamādhisukhañca.**The happiness of immersion and the happiness without immersion.*";
P_HTM[815]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve sukhāni.**These are the two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[816]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ sukhānaṃ yadidaṃ samādhisukhan”ti.**The better of these two kinds of happiness is the happiness of immersion.”*";
P_HTM[817]="*74**74*";
P_HTM[818]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, sukhāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[819]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[820]="*Sappītikārammaṇañca sukhaṃ nippītikārammaṇañca sukhaṃ.**Happiness that relies on rapture and happiness that relies on freedom from rapture.*";
P_HTM[821]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve sukhāni.**These are the two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[822]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ sukhānaṃ yadidaṃ nippītikārammaṇaṃ sukhan”ti.**The better of these two kinds of happiness is happiness that relies on freedom from rapture.”*";
P_HTM[823]="*75**75*";
P_HTM[824]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, sukhāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[825]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[826]="*Sātārammaṇañca sukhaṃ upekkhārammaṇañca sukhaṃ.**Happiness that relies on pleasure and happiness that relies on equanimity.*";
P_HTM[827]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve sukhāni.**These are the two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[828]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ sukhānaṃ yadidaṃ upekkhārammaṇaṃ sukhan”ti.**The better of these two kinds of happiness is happiness that relies on equanimity.”*";
P_HTM[829]="*76**76*";
P_HTM[830]="*“Dvemāni, bhikkhave, sukhāni.**“There are, mendicants, these two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[831]="*Katamāni dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[832]="*Rūpārammaṇañca sukhaṃ arūpārammaṇañca sukhaṃ.**Happiness that relies on form and happiness that relies on the formless.*";
P_HTM[833]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dve sukhāni.**These are the two kinds of happiness.*";
P_HTM[834]="*Etadaggaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ dvinnaṃ sukhānaṃ yadidaṃ arūpārammaṇaṃ sukhan”ti.**The better of these two kinds of happiness is happiness that relies on the formless.”*";
P_HTM[835]="*Sukhavaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[836]="*8. Sukkasuttaṃ**77*";
P_HTM[837]="*“Sanimittā, bhikkhave, uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā, no animittā.**“Bad, unskillful qualities, mendicants, arise with a foundation, not without a foundation.*";
P_HTM[838]="*Tasseva nimittassa pahānā evaṃ te pāpakā akusalā dhammā na hontī”ti.**By giving up that foundation, those bad, unskillful qualities do not occur.”*";
P_HTM[839]="*78**78*";
P_HTM[840]="*“Sanidānā, bhikkhave, uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā, no anidānā.**“Bad, unskillful qualities, mendicants, arise with a source, not without a source.*";
P_HTM[841]="*Tasseva nidānassa pahānā evaṃ te pāpakā akusalā dhammā na hontī”ti.**By giving up that source, those bad, unskillful qualities do not occur.”*";
P_HTM[842]="*79**79*";
P_HTM[843]="*“Sahetukā, bhikkhave, uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā, no ahetukā.**“Bad, unskillful qualities, mendicants, arise with a cause, not without a cause.*";
P_HTM[844]="*Tasseva hetussa pahānā evaṃ te pāpakā akusalā dhammā na hontī”ti.**By giving up that cause, those bad, unskillful qualities do not occur.”*";
P_HTM[845]="*80**80*";
P_HTM[846]="*“Sasaṅkhārā, bhikkhave, uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā, no asaṅkhārā.**“Bad, unskillful qualities, mendicants, arise with conditions, not without conditions.*";
P_HTM[847]="*Tesaṃyeva saṅkhārānaṃ pahānā evaṃ te pāpakā akusalā dhammā na hontī”ti.**By giving up those conditions, those bad, unskillful qualities do not occur.”*";
P_HTM[848]="*81**81*";
P_HTM[849]="*“Sappaccayā, bhikkhave, uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā, no appaccayā.**“Bad, unskillful qualities, mendicants, arise with a reason, not without a reason.*";
P_HTM[850]="*Tasseva paccayassa pahānā evaṃ te pāpakā akusalā dhammā na hontī”ti.**By giving up that reason, those bad, unskillful qualities do not occur.”*";
P_HTM[851]="*82**82*";
P_HTM[852]="*“Sarūpā, bhikkhave, uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā, no arūpā.**“Bad, unskillful qualities, mendicants, arise with form, not without form.*";
P_HTM[853]="*Tasseva rūpassa pahānā evaṃ te pāpakā akusalā dhammā na hontī”ti.**By giving up that form, those bad, unskillful qualities do not occur.”*";
P_HTM[854]="*83**83*";
P_HTM[855]="*“Savedanā, bhikkhave, uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā, no avedanā.**“Bad, unskillful qualities, mendicants, arise with feeling, not without feeling.*";
P_HTM[856]="*Tassāyeva vedanāya pahānā evaṃ te pāpakā akusalā dhammā na hontī”ti.**By giving up that feeling, those bad, unskillful qualities do not occur.”*";
P_HTM[857]="*84**84*";
P_HTM[858]="*“Sasaññā, bhikkhave, uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā, no asaññā.**“Bad, unskillful qualities, mendicants, arise with perception, not without perception.*";
P_HTM[859]="*Tassāyeva saññāya pahānā evaṃ te pāpakā akusalā dhammā na hontī”ti.**By giving up that perception, those bad, unskillful qualities do not occur.”*";
P_HTM[860]="*85**85*";
P_HTM[861]="*“Saviññāṇā, bhikkhave, uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā, no aviññāṇā.**“Bad, unskillful qualities, mendicants, arise with consciousness, not without consciousness.*";
P_HTM[862]="*Tasseva viññāṇassa pahānā evaṃ te pāpakā akusalā dhammā na hontī”ti.**By giving up that consciousness, those bad, unskillful qualities do not occur.”*";
P_HTM[863]="*86**86*";
P_HTM[864]="*“Saṅkhatārammaṇā, bhikkhave, uppajjanti pāpakā akusalā dhammā, no asaṅkhatārammaṇā.**“Bad, unskillful qualities, mendicants, arise with a conditioned basis, not without a conditioned basis.*";
P_HTM[865]="*Tasseva saṅkhatassa pahānā evaṃ te pāpakā akusalā dhammā na hontī”ti.**By giving up that conditioned basis, those bad, unskillful qualities do not occur.”*";
P_HTM[866]="*Sanimittavaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[867]="*9. Cariyasuttaṃ**87*";
P_HTM[868]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, dhammā.**“There are, mendicants, these two things.*";
P_HTM[869]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[870]="*Cetovimutti ca paññāvimutti ca.**Freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[871]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, dve dhammā”ti.**These are the two things.”*";
P_HTM[872]="*88**88*";
P_HTM[873]="*“Dveme, bhikkhave, dhammā.**“There are, mendicants, these two things.*";
